[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course I am going to provide you with a full repertoire against the English Opening. }
1. c4 e5
{ As early as move 1 we are at a corner. Generally, White wants to develop his kingside bishop with g3 and Bg2, however, he may do it with or without  2.Nc3  .   In the last part of the course we will also study rare 2nd moves, like  2.d3  @@StartBracket@@probably the most sensible move, willing to transpose into a reversed Najdorf or Classical Sicilian@@EndBracket@@,  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@GM Rakhmanov's specialty@@EndBracket@@ or  2.e3  @@StartBracket@@tried by Magnus with the move order  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.e3  @@EndBracket@@.   However, we will see that all of these lines aren't threatening for Black. }
2. Nc3
{ If White starts with  2.g3  then after  2...Nf6  Black will play 3...c6, never mind whether White plays  3.Bg2  or  3.Nc3  . Black's goal is to take control of the center with  3...c6  and  4.--  d5  .   In either case, White will then have to react in the center, thing which he can do either with 4.d4 or 4.Nf3.   In the event of  3.Nc3  c6  we are going to react to  4.d4  with  4...exd4  5.Qxd4  d5  , as in the event of an Isolated Pawn position @@StartBracket@@  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@, Black will be threatening to play ...Nc6 and ...d4, bothering the knight on c3.   And if:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2p2n2/4p3/2P5/2N3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  then our main line will go  4...e4  5.Nd4  Qb6!  bothering the white knight on d4, followed by ...d5, unless White goes for the main move  6.Nb3  in which case we will continue bothering the white knight with  6...a5!  with many complications to come,  7.d3  being the main move here.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2P5/6P1/PP1PPP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg2  c6  Again, White cannot just allow Black to push ...d5 and get a wonderful center. He should react either with 4.d4 or 4.Nf3.  4.Nf3   If  4.d4  now we are opting for  4...e4!  closing the position, with the idea of playing ...d5 next.   White will try to target our central pawns but won't succeed, as you'll discover in the course.  4...e4  5.Nd4  and here we will play similarly as in the same position with Nc3 being played instead of Bg2, except that we will start with  5...d5  6.cxd5  and now play  6...Qb6!  with the same idea of:  7.Nb3  a5!  threatening ...a4. Here the main line goes  8.d3  ,with complications that Black is perfectly able to handle. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 { With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...e4?!  is unfortunately dubious due to  4.Ng5  as the e4-pawn will fall since White can answer  4...Qe7  with  5.Qc2  .  However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit': @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/6N1/2P1p3/2N5/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5!?  But, of course, while it was a good try in the pre-computer era, this no longer can be considered a decent opening for Black. }
4. g3
{ The main move, playing a very Classical English opening. However, White has tried other interesting options here, the two main ones being  4.e4  and  4.e3  , both making ...d5 impossible/difficult to play.  Against both moves, we will react with  4...Bb4  , and throughout the course, you will discover a huge number of new and fun ideas.   Other rare moves are  4.d3  , but that will transpose into 2.d3, while  4.a3  , the last move we will examine, is not a threatening option. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ We now have a reversed Accelerated Dragon, and due to the missing bishop on e6, Nxe5 is already a tactical threat. }
6... Nb6 7. O-O Be7
{ Black develops calmly, and now White's most threatening plan is to try to expand on the queenside. }
8. a3
{ The critical move, trying to expand with b4. A typical Sicilian plan: which makes sense as the position is a reversed Sicilian!   8.d3  O-O  9.Be3  is another plan, against which I'll suggest to go  9...Re8!?  10.Rc1  Bf8  which I consider a very good setup for Black. }
8... O-O 9. b4
{ This is the very main line of the whole 1.c4 e5 opening! Now Black goes for a typical setup with ...Be6 and ...f6, and will jump to d4 with his c6-knight at some point. }
9... Be6 10. Rb1
{ We will see that this is the best move order, as it is important to cover the b3-square when the black knight jumps to d4.   We will also have a look at  10.d3  a5!  11.b5  Nd4  and see that the best White can do is to go  12.Rb1  f6  transposing into 10.Rb1. }
10... f6 11. d3
{ 11.b5  is a side line I discovered when Boris Gelfand played it against me at the European Team Championship 2017.  11...Nd4  12.e3  Nxf3+  13.Bxf3  Here I will give an overview of Black's possibilities but suggest you go to for an interesting pawn sac,  13...c6!? }
11... a5
{ It took me a lot of time to decide whether to include the moves ...a5 and b5 or not @@StartBracket@@in order words, first ...a5, or just ...Nd4@@EndBracket@@ but after deep analysis, I concluded that  11...a5  was easier to play, although I myself played  11...Nd4  several times, including a victory over Peter Svidler! }
12. b5 Nd4
{ The main advantage of having included ...a5 and b5 is that Black will often be able to fix the a3-weakness with ...a4.   The main disadvantage is that it makes the move ...c6, closing the g2-bishop's diagonal, more difficult to play. However, as you'll discover in the course, Black's position is full of play and even double-edged in many cases!   Have a good English Breakfast! }
*

