[Black "2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6
{ Any other move apart from  4.d4  - next subchapter - isn't dangerous, for example: }
4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. d3
{ Has been played more than 250 times, but Black is clearly sitting on the better side of the board. }
6... d4 { Any other 'normal' move like  6...Nc6  was perfectly fine as well. }
7. Ne4 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Be7 9. Bd2 Na6 { Aiming to go to c5. } 10. Bg2 O-O 11. Nf3
f6 12. O-O Be6
{ Black has extra space and perfectly placed pieces. Next is most probably ...Qd7 followed by a knight move. White is fighting for an equality he probably cannot reach. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6 4. Nf3
{ As explained in the introduction, White can't just allow Black to push ...d5 and enjoy a stable and superior center.   This and  4.d4  @@StartBracket@@next subchapter@@EndBracket@@ are the options to counter this plan. }
4... e4
{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. cxd5 Qb6
{ The best line, as the following variations prove.   We do want to take back on d5 with the pawn, but first we want to disturb the knight on d4, as it would stand on a nice outpost if Black takes ...cxd5 too quickly. The job couldn't be done with ...Bc5 as after Nb3 the black bishop would have been hanging.   6...cxd5?!  is not something I like either, for the reasons explained above:  7.d3  Bc5  8.Nb3  Bb4+  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  Re8  11.Be3  and I think the tension in the center favours White.   6...Qxd5  7.e3  leads to position I dislike, where White will open the center with Nc3 and d3, breaking the center and enjoying a lead in development: Black has moved his queens too many times! }
7. Nb3
{ 7.e3  cxd5  isn't a problem: the e3-pawn limits the c1-bishop and Black has nothing to worry about.   7.Qa4  Bc5  8.dxc6  O-O  9.e3  Rd8  and White is in trouble! His light squares are too weak. }
7... a5 { Threatening to trap the b3-knight with ...a4. } 8. a4 Nxd5
{ Active chess! Black sacrifices the e4-pawn to get a wonderfully active position.   8...cxd5  9.O-O  Na6  isn't any good, as Black is behind in development and after White breaks the center with  10.d3  , he will target Black's central pawns and have perfect squares for his pieces: Be3, Nc3, Nd4, Ndb5... }
9. O-O
{ 9.Bxe4  Bh3  would be a dream for Black: White being unable to castle. } 9...
Be6
{ Black needs to act dynamically. It looks to me like other moves do not equalize.   9...Nf6  to play ...Be6 next looks clever, but after  10.d4  Be6  11.N3d2  solves all the problems tactically, and after  11...Qxd4  12.Nxe4  Qxd1  13.Nxf6+  gxf6  14.Rxd1  Nd7  15.Be3  he just stands a bit better thanks to Black's doubled f-pawns.   A slow continuation would give White a more pleasant position, for example,  9...Be7  10.Na3  O-O  11.Nc4!   11.Bxe4  Nf6!  followed by ...Na6 is Bc2, or otherwise by ...Bh3 or ...Bh6, and Black has good compensation for the same reasons as after 9...Be6.  11...Qa6  is forced,  otherwise the e4–pawn is lost without compensation, as the b3–knight is no longer in danger.  12.d3  exd3  13.exd3↑  and despite a better pawn structure, the queen on a6 is very much out of play. }
10. Bxe4 { Now several moves lead to nice compensation. } 10... Nf6
{ 10...h5  11.d4  Nf6  12.Bc2  h4  with the idea of ...Na6-b4 would also be interesting: one does not play g3-Bg2 to end up with his bishop on c2! Obviously, White's king is very much weakened due to that misplaced bishop.   10...f5!?  would force White to take a decision with his bishop before moving the d5-knight, which could be a great advantage since after Bc2 Black will then be able to jump to b4. However, fortunately for White, he can play  11.Bxf5□  Bxf5  12.e4!  and after  12...Be6!  13.exd5  Bxd5  14.Re1+  Kf7  the position is a big mess, for example,  15.Re3  Nd7  16.d4  Bb4  and the position is just very difficult to assess, the engine giving around equality. White has an extra pawn but he is under-developed and Black has a powerful bishop on d5. }
11. Bc2 Na6 12. d4 Nb4 13. N1d2 h5
{ White is missing his fianchetto bishop so Black starts an attack. It is clear that White couldn't put his pieces on the desired square and that Black enjoys excellent coordination and compensation. }
*

