[Black "2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 c6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. d4 e4
{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 d5 6. cxd5
{ The main variation, though instead White may decide not to exchange on d5 prior to playing another move, keeping the tension, like in the lines below. }
6... cxd5 7. Bg5
{ 7.Qb3  no longer makes any sense, as Black will prevent Bg5 with  7...h6  and play ... Nc6 next, when White will have to play awkward moves to defend his d4-pawn. }
7... Bb4 8. Nh3
{ Again Black will take advantage of this move to go into the pawn structure he likes. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nbd7
{ Only if White had time to get his bishop to a3 before Black castles, Black would be in trouble. But he is far away from it @@StartBracket@@although just one move - but one move he will never ever have!@@EndBracket@@. }
10. f3 exf3 11. exf3 O-O 12. O-O h6
{ With the idea of ...Nb6 is a walk in the park for Black. } *

