1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ There are different possibilities against 2.d3, though this move hides much more venom than you may think at first.   As a matter of consistency, and also because I think it's the best line, I'll suggest playing a reversed Open Sicilian here as well. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here we have a reversed Najdorf Sicilian. } 6. e3
{ This is easier to meet: it is a slow move, which means that the extra tempo White got in a reversed Sicilian will matter less.   Here I'm going to suggest a setup I believe is very easy to handle as Black. }
6... Bd6 7. b4 O-O 8. Bb2 Re8 9. Be2 a5 10. b5 Na7
{ And White already has concrete problems with his b5-pawn, while after: } 11.
a4 c6 12. bxc6 Nxc6
{ Black is already slightly better thanks to the magnificent b4-square. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.d3 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ There are different possibilities against 2.d3, though this move hides much more venom than you may think at first.   As a matter of consistency, and also because I think it's the best line, I'll suggest playing a reversed Open Sicilian here as well. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ We have a reversed Classical Sicilian! } 6. e3
{ Allows Black a lot of choice @@StartBracket@@for example, a Classical System with ... Be7, ... Be6, ... O-O would be perfectly playable@@EndBracket@@, but again I would like to enter in a pawn structure we are familiar with, and than I do not consider threatening for Black. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O b6
{ Followed by ...Re8, ...Bb7, and again White has this very solid but inflexible center. We already discussed several times how to play against it in chapter 4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.d3 Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ There are different possibilities against 2.d3, though this move hides much more venom than you may think at first.   As a matter of consistency, and also because I think it's the best line, I'll suggest playing a reversed Open Sicilian here as well. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ We have a reversed Classical Sicilian! } 6. g3
{ A reversed Dragon Sicilian, which is absolutely not threatening here as Black will just pick a calm system, and obviously not enter extremely concrete lines a tempo down. }
6... Be7 7. Bg2 Be6
{ 7...Nb6  8.O-O  O-O  transposes into the very main lines of Part I, where White has played d3 a little too early:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.g3  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nb6  7.O-O  Be7  8.d3  O-O  . This is addressed in this variation. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Bd2 { 9.a3  a5  doesn't help White. } 9... Qd7
{ We have a reversed Dragon Sicilian with 6.Be2, where the lost tempo doesn't matter very much. Black does not have any problem here, for example: }
10. Rc1 f6 11. Ne4 Rfd8 12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. Rxc5 b6 14. Rc1 a5
{ Followed by something like ...Nce7 and ...c5. Black is more than okay here. }
