1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. Nc2
{ White spent three tempos in the opening to get his knight to c2. } 4... d5
{ Easiest and best. } 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc3 Qe5 7. d4
{ What else? Otherwise White just stands slightly worse after simple developing moves by Black. }
7... exd3 8. Qxd3 Nf6 9. e4 Nb4
{ The simplest, although the engine also likes  9...Bd7!?  . } 10. Nxb4 Bxb4
11. Qb5+ Qxb5 12. Bxb5+ Bd7
{ Many pieces got traded and Black is more active, sitting on the safe side of a nearly equal position. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@-Shyam,S @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ UAE 2014.   Stockfish's favorite  12...c6  is also possible  13.Bd3  Be6  14.f3  O-O-O  and Black is slightly better. }
