1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. e3
{ This move has become fashionable a few years ago, but lately it turned out what White had considered a symbolic advantage was in fact not even symbolic.   Here White allows  4...d5  , inviting Black to play a reversed Open Sicilian with extra tempo, but I am not going to advise it here, because the bishop would quickly go to b5 and create concrete problems for the e5-pawn. }
4... Bb4
{ The main and best move, I believe. Now we get some sort of reversed Rossolimo.   Pushing  4...e4  would have been too early due to  5.Ng5  , attacking the e5-pawn, but now Black does threaten to push ...e4 and then capture on c3, leaving the poor g5-knight a bit lonely and forced go to h3 if Black just attacks it. }
5. Qc2
{ The main move - defending against ...e4 and preparing to recapture on c3 with the queen. }
5... Bxc3
{ Black takes on c3 without even waiting for a3 to be played! Why?   First of all,  5...--  6.Nd5  had became a threat @@StartBracket@@  6...e4  just losing a pawn to  7.Nxf6+  and Qxe4+@@EndBracket@@. Secondly, Black is going to take advantage of the early developed white queen. }
6. Qxc3 Qe7 7. d4
{ Here the main line is  7...Ne4  followed by 8...exd4, with positions where Black most probably achieves equality. However, I believe closing the center with ...e4 is simply good for Back. }
7... e4 8. Nd2 d5 9. a3
{ 9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  a5  and the only piece Black will have to relocate at some point is the c6-knight, but Black has very easy moves to come: ...Re8, ...Bf5, possibly ...h5, ...h4, and I do not really see what White is doing. }
9... O-O
{ I beat GM Deac at the European Individual in Skopje, 2019, playing  9...a5  , which is also totally fine - but perhaps unnecessary as White played a3 to cover the b4-square, not necessarily to play b4 that would weaken the light-squares. }
10. h3
{ This was Studer's choice against me in a rapid online game.   If  10.b4  , for example  10...Qd8  with the idea of relocating the c6-knight through e7. In the game, I went  for @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp1qppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PPp3/P1Q1P2P/1P1N1PP1/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a5  , which again was not mandatory, I believe. }
10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 Be6
{ This is just very good for Black, whose plan is to go ...Nd5 and ...f5/...Qg5. }
