{ Other moves have no independent value, as Black would play ...d5 and play a reversed Sicilian where White got an extra useless @@StartBracket@@or even weakening@@EndBracket@@ move.   4.d3  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  just transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d3  Nf6  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Nc3  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  , covered in this line. }
4... d5
{ Against slow moves like a3, it is almost always a good solution to play ...g6. But, as a matter of consistency for this course, I'll just suggest to play a reversed Open Sicilian again. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qc2 Nxc3
{ Many other moves are possible, but I believe this is a simple solution. } 7.
dxc3 { Does not create any problem either. } 7... a5
{ Preventing White from expending on the queenside with b4. } 8. e4 Bc5 9. Bc4
Qf6 { Just picking a nice square for the black queen. } 10. a4 h6 11. O-O O-O
{ Here Black has nothing to worry about, easy moves to come like ...Ne7-g6, and no problems at all. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Four Knights Variation 4.e4"]
[Black "4.e4 Bb4 - 6.g3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. e4
{ An interesting move. White completely stops ...d7-d5 at the cost of the d4-square. Here, he takes advantage of two things: the knight on c6 prevents Black from pushing ...c6 and ...d5, and  4...Bc5  is quite dangerous for Black due to  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.d4  .   Thus, Black cannot take advantage of his edge on the dark squares that easily, meanwhile White will complete his development and play with a space advantage. }
4... Bb4
{ The best answer.   As I explained,  4...Bc5  5.Nxe5  is playable but dangerous for Black, while the other option is to play ...d6 and ...g6 and play some sort of King's Indian.   Instead, my suggestion is to go for the main move, 4...Bb4. Black's plan is pretty simple: besides potentially threatening to take on c3 and then on e4, he wants to play ...d6 and then move his bishop back to c5, as Nxe5 will no longer be a possibility. }
5. d3 d6 6. g3
{ Has been played quite a few times. White allows Black to trade the f3-knight and completely surrenders the control of the d4-square, but he wants to get the bishop pair and play for f2-f4 instead. }
6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nd4 9. Qd1
{ It may sound awkward to give to many tempos and the dark-squares, but the position remains unclear, and if White manages to complete his development @@StartBracket@@Bg2, O-O@@EndBracket@@ and push his kingside pawns, starting with f4, the black position could become quite dangerous to play. }
9... c6
{ Black wants to take control of the center, and possibly one day break it with ...d5 or even ...b5.   9...a5!?  in order to ensure the dark-squared bishop can never be exchanged after  10.a3  Bc5  is also highly interesting, according to the engine, and is a novelty.  However, I believe it makes even more sense to immediately take control of the center with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/1bPnP3/2NP2PP/PP3P2/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c6  the main recommendation in the course. }
10. Bg2 a5
{ Black wants to make sure the bishop won't be traded after it goes back to c5, as he now has an extra square on a7.   Instead,  10...a6  has been played more often, but the brand new engines believe that ...a5 is a better choice, which I easily believe, as it prevents White from gaining space with a3-b4. }
11. O-O Bc5
{ For now the f4-pawn cannot move before there would be a discovery check @@StartBracket@@e.g. ...Nb3+@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Kh2 { Would be inferior as after: } 12... h5 13. f4
{ Black would have extra tactics. } 13... Ng4+ 14. Kh1
{ And now after the simple: } 14... exf4 15. Bxf4
{ 15.gxf4?  Loses right away to:  15...Qh4  With the ideas of ...Qg3 or ...Nf2+. }
15... Qd7 { White is sort of paralyzed. } *

