12. Kh1 { Definitely the right square for the king, as the alternative shows. }
12... h5
{ A good move anyway! Black wants to push ...h4, force g4 and increase his control of the dark squares. }
13. f4
{ 13.h4  Qd7  Would just be easy for Black, for the simple reason that now f4 would give away a very important square on g4. White no longer has a plan. }
13... h4 14. g4 Nd7
{ Black wants to take on f4 and set a knight on e5, and this is the best move order.   If  14...exf4  15.Bxf4  Nd7  wouldn't be necessarily bad, but would allow  16.Na4  capturing the dark-squared bishop due to the hanging pawn on d6 if the bishop moves. }
15. f5
{ After basically any other move, Black would take on f4 and play ...Ne5, with a slightly better position. However, this is even more unprecise. }
15... g5
{ The point - otherwise White would push g5 himself with a strong initiative. Black wants to push ...f6, blocking the kingside where White was putting all his hopes, and is positionally clearly better. }
16. fxg6 fxg6
{ Black will play ....Qe7, ...Rf8, and again enjoys a clear positional advantage with no counterplay for White. It remains unclear whether Black will castle queenside or move his king to the kingside after swapping rooks on the f-file. }
