[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Four Knights Variation 4.e4"]
[Black "4.e4 Bb4 - 6.a3 Bc5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. e4
{ An interesting move. White completely stops ...d7-d5 at the cost of the d4-square. Here, he takes advantage of two things: the knight on c6 prevents Black from pushing ...c6 and ...d5, and  4...Bc5  is quite dangerous for Black due to  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.d4  .   Thus, Black cannot take advantage of his edge on the dark squares that easily, meanwhile White will complete his development and play with a space advantage. }
4... Bb4
{ The best answer.   As I explained,  4...Bc5  5.Nxe5  is playable but dangerous for Black, while the other option is to play ...d6 and ...g6 and play some sort of King's Indian.   Instead, my suggestion is to go for the main move, 4...Bb4. Black's plan is pretty simple: besides potentially threatening to take on c3 and then on e4, he wants to play ...d6 and then move his bishop back to c5, as Nxe5 will no longer be a possibility. }
5. d3 d6 6. a3
{ Other moves give Black enough time to get a full control of the d4-square @@StartBracket@@especially if White allows ...Bg4@@EndBracket@@ and a very healthy position. }
6... Bc5 7. b4 Bb6 8. Na4
{ White wants to capture the bishop pair, before Black plays ...Bg4 or any other move that would allow the b6-bishop to stay alive.   The calmer alternative  8.Be3  , also taking control of the d4-square, is a little more peaceful. }
8... Bg4
{ The most logical move: White removes the b6-bishop, a strong asset for the control of the d4-square, and Black does the same thing, eliminating the f3-knight.   Instead,  8...Bd4  is fully playable, while other players simply castled but I believe White ends up slightly better there. }
9. Be2
{ White delays the exchange on b6, allowing Black to actually remove is bishop from there. }
9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Bd4 11. Rb1 a6
{ There is nothing wrong with  11...O-O  , but starting with ...a6 immediately is more to my taste, granting an extra square for the black bishop on a7, and threatening to push ...b5. }
12. Bd2 Ba7 { Making room for the c6-knight to jump to d4. } 13. g3
{ White wants to relocate his bishop to g2 to later play O-O, Kh1, and push f4. }
13... Nd4 14. Bg2 h5
{ The correct reaction!   Now White has a painful decision to make: if he allows ...h4, the h-file will open whenever he castles and f4 will never happen. If he plays h3 he allows ...h4, creating extra holes on the dark squares.   Finally, he can play  15.h4  , a healthy move, but again it will be very difficult to push f4 as the g4-square will then be a perfect spot for the f6-knight. In order words, three choices, and all of them are bad! }
15. h3
{ White wants to be able to counter ...h4 with g4, without allowing the black pawn to h3 - a typical prophylaxis.   15.h4  White gives away the g4-square, but there is no reason to jump there so early.  15...Ng4  16.O-O  Qf6  17.c5!  Qg6  18.f3  Nh6  19.Kh2  turned into White's favour in the game Esipenko, A @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@-Najer, E @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2020, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@. }
15... h4 16. g4 Nh7 { Bringing the knight to e6 through g5. } 17. O-O Ng5 18.
Nc3 c6 19. Kh1 Nge6
{ We are following a game of mine, where I got a perfect control of the dark squares. }
20. Ne2 Qf6
{ 20...g5!  may simply have been a strategically winning position, but I was afraid to block the position too much and then be unable to break it. No doubt White is much worse, but now the game will have to be won on the queenside. }
21. g5 Nxg5
{ The correct move!   21...Qe7?!  A dubious decision from my side.  22.Nxd4  Bxd4  Now I got much better again and went on winning the game. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Mousavi, S @@StartBracket@@2432@@EndBracket@@-Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2639@@EndBracket@@ Iran 2016.   22.f4  would have turned the position into a mess. }
22. f4 Nxe2 23. Qxe2 Ne6 24. f5 Nf4
{ Giving the pawn back to increase my control of the dark squares. } 25. Bxf4
exf4 26. Rxf4 Qe5 { With a clear advantage for Black. } *

