{ The most logical move: White removes the b6-bishop, a strong asset for the control of the d4-square, and Black does the same thing, eliminating the f3-knight.   Instead,  8...Bd4  is fully playable, while other players simply castled but I believe White ends up slightly better there. }
9. Be2
{ White delays the exchange on b6, allowing Black to actually remove is bishop from there. }
9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Bd4 11. Rb1 a6
{ There is nothing wrong with  11...O-O  , but starting with ...a6 immediately is more to my taste, granting an extra square for the black bishop on a7, and threatening to push ...b5. }
12. Bd2 Ba7 { Making room for the c6-knight to jump to d4. } 13. g3
{ White wants to relocate his bishop to g2 to later play O-O, Kh1, and push f4. }
13... Nd4 14. Bg2 h5
{ The correct reaction!   Now White has a painful decision to make: if he allows ...h4, the h-file will open whenever he castles and f4 will never happen. If he plays h3 he allows ...h4, creating extra holes on the dark squares.   Finally, he can play  15.h4  , a healthy move, but again it will be very difficult to push f4 as the g4-square will then be a perfect spot for the f6-knight. In order words, three choices, and all of them are bad! }
