{ White gives away the g4-square, but there is no reason to jump there so early. }
15... O-O 16. O-O Ng4
{ Now is a fine time to do it. Let me show you two fun attacking ideas. } 17.
Nc3
{ 17.c5  is no longer a problem, as Black can simply go ...Ne6, for example, putting pressure on the c5-pawn in order to open the bishop's diagonal again.   17.Kh1  Ne6  18.Qe2  Nf4!  A cute move, gxf4 being impossible due to ...Qxh4+ followed by a checkmate on h3.  19.Qf3  Nxg2  20.Kxg2  and White survived - but no more than this. }
17... f5
{ Black opens the f-file in order to increase the pressure on the f2-pawn. }
18. Bg5 Qd7 19. exf5 Nxf5 20. Ne4
{ A necessary move, the knight being a crucial defender of both the f2 and g3 pawns! }
20... c6 21. Bh3 Nd4 22. Bg2 Ne6
{ With ...d5 to come, and again, it's clearly White who is trying to equalize. }
