[Round "?"]
[White "1) Four Knights Variation 4.e4"]
[Black "4.e4 Bb4 - 6.a3 Bc5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. e4
{ An interesting move. White completely stops ...d7-d5 at the cost of the d4-square. Here, he takes advantage of two things: the knight on c6 prevents Black from pushing ...c6 and ...d5, and  4...Bc5  is quite dangerous for Black due to  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.d4  .   Thus, Black cannot take advantage of his edge on the dark squares that easily, meanwhile White will complete his development and play with a space advantage. }
4... Bb4
{ The best answer.   As I explained,  4...Bc5  5.Nxe5  is playable but dangerous for Black, while the other option is to play ...d6 and ...g6 and play some sort of King's Indian.   Instead, my suggestion is to go for the main move, 4...Bb4. Black's plan is pretty simple: besides potentially threatening to take on c3 and then on e4, he wants to play ...d6 and then move his bishop back to c5, as Nxe5 will no longer be a possibility. }
5. d3 d6 6. a3
{ Other moves give Black enough time to get a full control of the d4-square @@StartBracket@@especially if White allows ...Bg4@@EndBracket@@ and a very healthy position. }
6... Bc5 7. b4 Bb6 8. Na4
{ White wants to capture the bishop pair, before Black plays ...Bg4 or any other move that would allow the b6-bishop to stay alive.   The calmer alternative  8.Be3  , also taking control of the d4-square, is a little more peaceful. }
8... Bg4
{ The most logical move: White removes the b6-bishop, a strong asset for the control of the d4-square, and Black does the same thing, eliminating the f3-knight.   Instead,  8...Bd4  is fully playable, while other players simply castled but I believe White ends up slightly better there. }
9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Bb2 Nd7
{ Black starts to manoeuvre his knight towards e6, where it will have a wonderful control of the d4-square. }
11. Be2 h5
{ An awesome plan I discovered when working on the course - that has already been played by Karjakin!   The following moves and their annotations will help you to understand the point of this weird move. }
12. O-O Bxf3
{ Black should get rid off that knight before it is too late   12...Qf6?  is definitely not the move order:  13.Ne1  Bxe2  14.Qxe2  Nd4  15.Bxd4  exd4  16.f4  and White was much better in the game Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ -Karjakin, S @@StartBracket@@2752@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com 2020, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bxf3 Qf6 14. Be2
{ If he could do all at once, Black would like to play ...Nf8, ... Ne6, and then consider what to do with his g-pawn. But now, he must act against the f4-threat.   14.Bxh5?  loses right away to  14...Qh6  or  14...Qh4  . }
14... g5 15. Bxh5 { The pawn grab is still bad. } 15... Qh6 16. g4 Nf6
{ With a huge advantage for Black. } *

