11. Be2 h5
{ An awesome plan I discovered when working on the course - that has already been played by Karjakin!   The following moves and their annotations will help you to understand the point of this weird move. }
12. O-O Bxf3
{ Black should get rid off that knight before it is too late   12...Qf6?  is definitely not the move order:  13.Ne1  Bxe2  14.Qxe2  Nd4  15.Bxd4  exd4  16.f4  and White was much better in the game Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ -Karjakin, S @@StartBracket@@2752@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com 2020, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bxf3 Qf6 14. Be2
{ If he could do all at once, Black would like to play ...Nf8, ... Ne6, and then consider what to do with his g-pawn. But now, he must act against the f4-threat.   14.Bxh5?  loses right away to  14...Qh6  or  14...Qh4  . }
14... g5 15. Qd2 Nf8 16. f4
{ Just in time! Otherwise Black would play ...Ne6 and be clearly better, as he would also have a full control of the kingside. }
16... gxf4 17. Qxf4 Qxf4 18. Rxf4 Ng6
{ Managing to play f4 was definitely a success for White. Still, it doesn't bring him more than equality. }
19. Rf5
{ The only threatening move, but Black has different ways to equalize here. }
19... Rh7
{ A cute tactical solution to Black's minor problems.   19...Nd4  is not advisable:  20.Bxd4  exd4  21.Bxh5  Ne5  22.Be2  and Black does have compensation, but he isn't playing for an advantage here. }
20. Raf1 { Now allows: } 20... Nd4 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Bxh5 Ne5
{ Not only d3 is hanging, but also a3. } *

