{ Looks natural, but now allows Black to push ...e4 in dream conditions, forcing the f3-knight to move backwards. }
5... e4 6. Ng1 { 6.Ng5??  Nxd5  and the g5-knight is hanging. } 6... O-O
{ Here White has three main options. } 7. a3 Bd6
{ The best square for the bishop - supporting the move ...Ne5 when White's g1-knight will come to f3. }
8. d3 exd3
{ The easiest move, but  8...b6!?  or  8...Re8!?  also deserve attention. } 9.
Nf3
{ A smart move, as capturing on d3 right away would allow ...Ne5, gaining a tempo on the light-squared bishop. }
9... Ne5
{ Black starts trading pieces and the position will soon clarify as approximately equal. }
10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Bxd3 c6
{ Now White has a choice: a natural move, or a tactical one. } 12. f4 Bd4
{ An awesome move! Not making the mistake to retract the bishop on b8 as GM Sargsyan did. }
13. Bc2
{ 13.exd4  cxd5  is simply better for Black, who has big problems on the light squares. }
13... cxd5 14. Qxd4 dxc4 15. Qxc4 b5 { Is a very interesting alternative. } 16.
Qxb5 Qc7
{ Engine stuff!   If  17.Qe2  then  17...Ba6  and Black has enough compensation. }
17. Bd3 a5
{ Playing ...Ba6 remains the key - most probably followed by ...Re8. Black has enough compensation.   ½-½ @@StartBracket@@103@@EndBracket@@ Santos Ruiz, M @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@-Dubov, D @@StartBracket@@2703@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019 }
*

