5. Qc2
{ The main move - defending against ...e4 and preparing to recapture on c3 with the queen. }
5... Bxc3
{ Black takes on c3 without even waiting for a3 to be played! Why?   First of all,  5...--  6.Nd5  had became a threat @@StartBracket@@  6...e4  just losing a pawn to  7.Nxf6+  and Qxe4+@@EndBracket@@. Secondly, Black is going to take advantage of the early developed white queen. }
6. Qxc3 Qe7 7. b3
{ This move, also waiting for Black to push ...d5 before playing d4, had became very fashionable in the years 2018-2020. However, I almost gave it a '?!' mark, as I believe it gives Black the initiative. While in the main lines of this chapter Black should be precise to equalize, here I believe it is White who should be precise. }
7... d5 8. d4
{ In this exact position, Black has several options proving 7.b3 to be too slow, although objectively, White may be okay with accurate play.   I'll show you two ideas I like very much - but two other interesting moves are  8...Bf5  and  8...Ne4  . }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 c5
{ Black goes for the typical plan, and White is hoping that developing his bishop on b2 quickly will handicap Black. }
11. Qf4 g5
{ Boom! Welcome to the world of engines!   Before White gets time to develop his dark-squared bishop on b2, the engines puts fire on board, disturbs the white queen, opens the g-file, after what Black will be able to create problems on the g-file but also on the h8-a1 diagonal.   Furthermore, the g-file being opened, it's unclear where the white king is going to be safe! Such a move is possible because 7.b3 has been too slow and Black is actively taking advantage of it. }
12. Qxg5 Rg8 13. Qf4 { Again the only move, otherwise 13...Qe5 is a killer. }
13... Nh5 14. Qh6 Qe5
{ Once more - White deeply regrets to have moved his b2-pawn. } 15. Rb1 Rg6 16.
Qxh7 Nf6
{ The safe bet - a draw.   But  16...Nf4  and  16...d4  deserve high attention as well. }
17. Qh8+ Rg8 18. Qh4
{ Best for White is to try to provoke a move repetition, and objectively Black has equally good alternatives, but luckily for him, White is not worse. }
18... Rg4
{ With a draw.   If  18...Bf5  ,  Black tries to provoke White a little bit though.  19.Bb2  d4  20.Rd1  .  All these White moves are forced - on the other hand they are also quite obvious.  20...O-O-O  21.Be2  is also unclear, again here Black has many moves, taking on g2 only being one of them!   If  @@StartFEN@@r3k1r1/pp3p2/5n2/2p1qb2/2Pp3Q/1P2P3/PB3PPP/3RKB1R b Kq - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20...Rg4  21.Qh8+  Rg8  22.Qh4  with a draw. }
