6. Qxc3 Qe7 7. d4
{ Here the main line is  7...Ne4  followed by 8...exd4, with positions where Black most probably achieves equality. However, I believe closing the center with ...e4 is simply good for Back. }
7... e4 8. Nd2 d5 9. a3
{ 9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  a5  and the only piece Black will have to relocate at some point is the c6-knight, but Black has very easy moves to come: ...Re8, ...Bf5, possibly ...h5, ...h4, and I do not really see what White is doing. }
9... O-O
{ I beat GM Deac at the European Individual in Skopje, 2019, playing  9...a5  , which is also totally fine - but perhaps unnecessary as White played a3 to cover the b4-square, not necessarily to play b4 that would weaken the light-squares. }
10. h3
{ This was Studer's choice against me in a rapid online game.   If  10.b4  , for example  10...Qd8  with the idea of relocating the c6-knight through e7. In the game, I went  for @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp1qppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PPp3/P1Q1P2P/1P1N1PP1/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a5  , which again was not mandatory, I believe. }
10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 Be6
{ This is just very good for Black, whose plan is to go ...Nd5 and ...f5/...Qg5. }
