14. Qe4 Bd7 15. Qc4 Bxb5 16. Qxb5 Rd8 17. O-O b6
{ And Black's next moves might be ...f5/...f6, ...Kf7, ...Qd7, with just a fine position, e.g. }
18. Rd1 f5 19. Bd2 Kf7
{ With equality. Black is likely to double rooks on the d-file with ...Rd7 and ...Rhd8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Four Knights Variation 4.e3"]
[Black "5.Qc2 Bxc3 - 7.Be2 | Alternative 7...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the most interesting move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. e3
{ This move has become fashionable a few years ago, but lately it turned out what White had considered a symbolic advantage was in fact not even symbolic.   Here White allows  4...d5  , inviting Black to play a reversed Open Sicilian with extra tempo, but I am not going to advise it here, because the bishop would quickly go to b5 and create concrete problems for the e5-pawn. }
4... Bb4
{ The main and best move, I believe. Now we get some sort of reversed Rossolimo.   Pushing  4...e4  would have been too early due to  5.Ng5  , attacking the e5-pawn, but now Black does threaten to push ...e4 and then capture on c3, leaving the poor g5-knight a bit lonely and forced go to h3 if Black just attacks it. }
5. Qc2
{ The main move - defending against ...e4 and preparing to recapture on c3 with the queen. }
5... Bxc3
{ Black takes on c3 without even waiting for a3 to be played! Why?   First of all,  5...--  6.Nd5  had became a threat @@StartBracket@@  6...e4  just losing a pawn to  7.Nxf6+  and Qxe4+@@EndBracket@@. Secondly, Black is going to take advantage of the early developed white queen. }
6. Qxc3 Qe7 7. Be2
{ White calmly develops before playing d4, which he will end up playing anyway. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ 8.d4  e4  followed by ...d5 would get us to similar positions as in the above lines  (7th move alternatives)  , which I definitely think are okay for Black. }
8... d5 9. d4 { Would now allow: } 9... Bg4
{ With a great position for Black. } *

