[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6 4. g3
{ The main line and most common way to play for White: developing the bishop on g2. Now my advice is to enter the main lines, as ...c6 and ...d5 are no longer possible. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6
{ A useful move to avoid tactical tricks like Nxe5, or positional threats like d4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3
{ Against this slow plan, I will advise a different setup for Black, which I believe is easy to play, and a better answer to potential d3-d4 ideas, as Black immediately centralizes his f8-rook, unlike other lines that we have seen and those that we will see later in the chapter. }
9... Re8 10. a4
{ This was tried by Wesley So. Black can play ...a5 and later make sure of the b4-square, but why give away the b5-square when the one on b4 is already already available? }
10... Bb4
{ Black is just fine. Moving the knight to a2 wouldn't bring White anything after ...Bf8, while:   10...a6?!  was a very bad reaction from Black in the game, as White could gain a lot of space and the black pieces became miscoordinated:  11.a5  Nd7  (So-Ganguly 2018)  and here after  12.d4  exd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  I believe White would simply be clearly better, e.g.  14...c6  15.Qc2  followed by Rfd1, Ne4... }
11. d4 { The pawn push is easily met. } 11... Nc4 12. dxe5 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Qxd1
14. Rfxd1 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Na5
{ @@StartBracket@@With the idea of ...Be6@@EndBracket@@   If we play directly  15...Be6  this allow White to exchange pieces and ease his position with  16.Nd4  .  After 15...Na5, Black definitely has enough compensation, the only concrete possible line here being: }
16. Rd5 b6 { It is good that the d5-rook sorts of blocks the h1-a8 diagonal. }
17. Nd4 Rb8 18. Nb5 { A weird but concrete move. } 18... c6 19. Nc7 Rf8 20. Rd6
Rb7 21. Na6 Re7
{ Which is absolutely fine for Black, who will win the e5-pawn. } *

