10. d3 a5
{ A good thing about this chapter - we always play ...a5 and then ...Nd4, so there's no need to remember when ...a5 should be included or not!   10...Nd4  11.Bb2  Bb3  used to be what Black loved to do, as after  12.Qd2  he has a nice trick being  12...Nc4!  However, after:  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/1n6/4p3/1P1n4/PbNP1NP1/1B2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qc1  Nxf3+  13.Bxf3  c6  14.Rb1  followed by either b5 or Ne4, I am not sure Black can equalize. }
11. b5 Nd4
{ Now Black already threatens to win the bishop pair with ...Nb3. Another annoying move could be ...Bb3.   Last but not least, Black has saved the ...f6 tempo as after  12.Nxe5  Bf6  , the hanging knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@as there is no pawn on d2@@EndBracket@@ changes everything. }
12. Bb2 Nb3 13. Rb1 f6
{ The most simple way to play. The b2-bishop is kind of annoyed by the b3-knight, Black can easily defend against a move like Nh4 just playing ... Nc5, while the simple knight trade: }
14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Nc4 16. Qc2 Nxb2 17. Qxb2 Rb8
{ The position is entirely fine for Black. Next is ...Qd7 or ...Qd6, possibly ...Kh8, possibly ...f5, and Black is definitely on the good side of things. }
