1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6 4. g3
{ The main line and most common way to play for White: developing the bishop on g2. Now my advice is to enter the main lines, as ...c6 and ...d5 are no longer possible. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6
{ A useful move to avoid tactical tricks like Nxe5, or positional threats like d4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. a3
{ The critical move, trying to expend with b4. A typical Sicilian plan: which makes sense as the position is a reversed Sicilian! }
8... O-O 9. b4 Be6
{ 9...Re8  10.d3  Bf8  is also a possible plan here, but I don't think it's best. For example, after  11.Bb2  a5  12.b5  Nd4  13.Nd2  White never trades this knight, otherwise he's simplifying Black's life very much - there would be no knight coming to c4, to start with.  13...a4  14.e3  Ne6  15.Nc4  Nc5  16.Nxe5  Rxe5  17.d4  White does have a slight advantage. However, it is highly probable that this line is also possible to improve for Black, for  example with @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/1pp2ppp/1n6/pP2p3/3n4/P1NP2P1/1B1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c6!? }
10. Rb1 { The best move order, covering the b3-square. } 10... f6
{ I discovered the following idea when Boris Gelfand played it against me at the European Team Championship 2017. }
11. b5 Nd4 12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3
{ At first, I must admit I was very surprised, as it looked to me totally harmless. In fact, it is a quite serious idea for White and Black should be precise. }
13... c6
{ A very interesting pawn sac that Nakamura played against Dubov. The latter repeated that line quite often as White after Gelfand sort of re-invented it!   13...Qc8  Followed by ...Rd8 is the move I first wanted to suggest, and I believe it is highly interesting as well, but after investigation, I considered 13...c6 a simpler answer.   13...Bc4  14.Bxb7  Bxf1  15.Qxf1  is definitely something I didn't want: the light-squared bishop is Black's most important piece in the position, keeping control of the center and keeping an eye on both sides of the board. It is not worth a rook, but White also got the b7-pawn, which tips the scale in White's favour.   13...Rb8  was by choice against Gelfand, but after  14.d4  and soon a4, I ended up slightly worse. Carlsen also beat Topalov two years later. It could be that Black holds in this line, but this is not the one I would advise.   I quite dislike  13...Nd5  because of  14.Ne2  with the idea of d2-d4, although I had this position with White, and after an excellent game my opponent managed to get out with a draw @@StartBracket@@Edouard-Xiong 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
14. bxc6 bxc6 { It could be that the best is to decline that pawn sac. } 15.
Bxc6 Rc8 16. Bb7 Rc7 17. Ba6
{ Trying to prevent ...Qd3, dominating the light squares. } 17... Bf5 18. Ra1
Qd7 19. Re1 Rd8
{ White is sort of paralyzed and pays the bill for not having moved his d2-pawn earlier. The c1-bishop is sort of trapped and Black had excellent compensation in the game: Dubov, D @@StartBracket@@2699@@EndBracket@@ -Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com 2020, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@. }
*

