{ I discovered the following idea when Boris Gelfand played it against me at the European Team Championship 2017. }
11. b5 Nd4 12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3
{ At first, I must admit I was very surprised, as it looked to me totally harmless. In fact, it is a quite serious idea for White and Black should be precise. }
13... c6
{ A very interesting pawn sac that Nakamura played against Dubov. The latter repeated that line quite often as White after Gelfand sort of re-invented it!   13...Qc8  Followed by ...Rd8 is the move I first wanted to suggest, and I believe it is highly interesting as well, but after investigation, I considered 13...c6 a simpler answer.   13...Bc4  14.Bxb7  Bxf1  15.Qxf1  is definitely something I didn't want: the light-squared bishop is Black's most important piece in the position, keeping control of the center and keeping an eye on both sides of the board. It is not worth a rook, but White also got the b7-pawn, which tips the scale in White's favour.   13...Rb8  was by choice against Gelfand, but after  14.d4  and soon a4, I ended up slightly worse. Carlsen also beat Topalov two years later. It could be that Black holds in this line, but this is not the one I would advise.   I quite dislike  13...Nd5  because of  14.Ne2  with the idea of d2-d4, although I had this position with White, and after an excellent game my opponent managed to get out with a draw @@StartBracket@@Edouard-Xiong 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
14. bxc6 bxc6 { It could be that the best is to decline that pawn sac. } 15. d4
{ The move Dubov had chosen in 2017, when in 2020 he took the pawn on c3 against Nakamura. The fact he did not repeat should probably means that Black is able to equalize here, and most probably what follows is one of the ways. }
15... Qd7
{ After this novelty, I believe Black is okay.   After  15...exd4  , Pashikian somehow never managed to equalize, as he was missing one tempo all the way.  16.exd4  Qd7  17.Re1  Nd5  18.Qb3  . Perhaps not the best move, as here the engine claims if  18...Rab8  or  18...Rfb8  , Black is doing fine, while he wasn't half a move before.  18...Rad8  19.Rb2  Bf7  20.Nxd5  Bxd5  21.Bxd5+  cxd5  22.Rbe2  Rf7  23.h4  Bf8  24.Bd2  Black's position is extremely unpleasant. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Dubov, D @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@-Pashikian, A @@StartBracket@@2603@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2017. }
16. dxe5
{ An isolated pawn on e5 is normally what Black wants to avoid, additionally to the one on c6. But here, I believe he is dynamic enough to compensate for both of these long-term weaknesses.   Other white moves clearly can't pose serious problems, e.g. White cannot put pressure on the e-file as in the game Dubov-Pashikian @@StartBracket@@15...exd4@@EndBracket@@. }
16... fxe5 17. Qxd7 Bxd7 18. Be4
{ The c1-bishop is White's big problem, and I repeat: it compensates for the black weaknesses. }
18... Be6
{ White could also start with a move like  18...Rab8  , but here the c6-pawn is not hanging due to ...Rac8. }
19. a4 Rab8 20. a5 Nc4 { And the a5-pawn is likely to be lost. } *

