{ A useful move to avoid tactical tricks like Nxe5, or positional threats like d4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. a3
{ The critical move, trying to expend with b4. A typical Sicilian plan: which makes sense as the position is a reversed Sicilian! }
8... O-O 9. b4 Be6
{ 9...Re8  10.d3  Bf8  is also a possible plan here, but I don't think it's best. For example, after  11.Bb2  a5  12.b5  Nd4  13.Nd2  White never trades this knight, otherwise he's simplifying Black's life very much - there would be no knight coming to c4, to start with.  13...a4  14.e3  Ne6  15.Nc4  Nc5  16.Nxe5  Rxe5  17.d4  White does have a slight advantage. However, it is highly probable that this line is also possible to improve for Black, for  example with @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/1pp2ppp/1n6/pP2p3/3n4/P1NP2P1/1B1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c6!? }
10. Rb1 { The best move order, covering the b3-square. } 10... f6 11. d3 a5
{ After spending countless hours refreshing my knowledge of the line  11...Nd4  , a move I played several times and even beat Svidler with, I realized that  11...a5  was a much simpler way to equalize! }
12. b5 Nd4
{ The advantage for Black of including the moves ...a5 and b5 is that the b5-pawn could be a target, and that ...a4 becomes a possibility. The disadvantage is that he cannot solidly play ...c6. }
13. e3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Qc8
{ Followed by ...Rd8 is harmless for White, who will have to push d4 eventually and will just get a very bad version of the 11.b5 Nd4 12.e3 line: first of all he used two tempi to push d4, secondly, the pawn on a5 is a great thing for Black, as the main plan for White in the 11.b5 line was to play a4-a5. }
