4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6
{ A useful move to avoid tactical tricks like Nxe5, or positional threats like d4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. a3
{ The critical move, trying to expend with b4. A typical Sicilian plan: which makes sense as the position is a reversed Sicilian! }
8... O-O 9. b4 Be6
{ 9...Re8  10.d3  Bf8  is also a possible plan here, but I don't think it's best. For example, after  11.Bb2  a5  12.b5  Nd4  13.Nd2  White never trades this knight, otherwise he's simplifying Black's life very much - there would be no knight coming to c4, to start with.  13...a4  14.e3  Ne6  15.Nc4  Nc5  16.Nxe5  Rxe5  17.d4  White does have a slight advantage. However, it is highly probable that this line is also possible to improve for Black, for  example with @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/1pp2ppp/1n6/pP2p3/3n4/P1NP2P1/1B1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c6!? }
10. Rb1 { The best move order, covering the b3-square. } 10... f6 11. d3 a5
{ After spending countless hours refreshing my knowledge of the line  11...Nd4  , a move I played several times and even beat Svidler with, I realized that  11...a5  was a much simpler way to equalize! }
12. b5 Nd4
{ The advantage for Black of including the moves ...a5 and b5 is that the b5-pawn could be a target, and that ...a4 becomes a possibility. The disadvantage is that he cannot solidly play ...c6. }
13. Nd2 Qc8
{ The best way to defend the b7-pawn. Furthermore, Black now has an extra option of playing ...Bh3 to exchange White's monster bishop on g2. }
14. e3 Nf5 15. Qc2 { This is the way everyone plays as White. } 15... a4
{ This move, played by Anish Giri, is a very interesting alternative to the main move  15...Rd8  .   Black immediately paralyzes White on the queenside, and the long term target is the a3-pawn. Black wants to play ...Rd8 or ...Nd6 followed by ...Bh3 next. }
16. Nc4
{ An interesting pawn sacrifice - and I would say it is difficult to find another useful move for White. If Back takes the pawn, White could soon put his knight on d5 and create problems. }
16... Rd8
{ Although it would probably not be bad either to accept the gift, I believe this is a much easier way to play for Black. }
17. Qe2
{ Here Black has many ways to play @@StartBracket@@e.g.  17...Bf8  ,  17...Kh8  , or any healthy move@@EndBracket@@, but an interesting plan is to bring the f5-knight to f7, also freeing the e6-h3 diagonal for the light-squared bishop.   17.Nxb6  cxb6  doubles Black's pawns, but ...Bb3 is coming and White will have serious problems on the c-file. }
17... Nh6 18. e4
{ The only way White can try to take advantage of ...Nh6 as ...Nd4 is no longer possible. }
18... Nxc4 19. dxc4 c6 { Black does not fear the capture on h6. } 20. Bxh6 gxh6
{ The d4-square and the dark squares in general largely compensate for the doubled h-pawns. Next is, most likely,  21.--  Rd4  . }
*

