[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 4.a3 Reversed Open Sicilian Setup"]
[Black "4.a3 d5 - 6.e4 Nxc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, White prevents ...c6, ...d5 ideas. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...e4  4.Ng5  simply doesn't work for Black, as Qc2 is coming and the e4-pawn will fall.   However, one funny thing to be noted is that the best move here is the 'Bellon Lopez Gambit':  4...b5!?  . But, of course, it is known to be very dubious. }
4. a3
{ Other moves have no independent value, as Black would play ...d5 and play a reversed Sicilian where White got an extra useless @@StartBracket@@or even weakening@@EndBracket@@ move.   4.d3  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  just transposes to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/8/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.d3  Nf6  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.Nc3  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  , covered in this line. }
4... d5
{ Against slow moves like a3, it is almost always a good solution to play ...g6. But, as a matter of consistency for this course, I'll just suggest to play a reversed Open Sicilian again. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4
{ White plays a reversed Sveshnikov Sicilian, where a3 is definitely useful as in the real Sveshnikov White would play Ndb5 @@StartBracket@@...Ndb4 not being possible here@@EndBracket@@. However, as Black, we only need to equalize, and here I'm going to suggest two solutions for that. }
6... Nxc3
{ 6...Nf4!?  7.d4  exd4  8.Bxf4  dxc3  9.Qxd8+  Nxd8  10.bxc3  Ne6  is also completely fine for Black. }
7. bxc3 Bd6 8. d4 O-O { 8...Qe7  would allow the annoying  9.Bb5  . } 9. Be2
Qe7
{ Is just better for Black already, and White should worry about his e4-pawn.   If White closes the center with  10.d5  , Black will put his knight on a5 and happily push ...f5 sooner or later, as well as ...b6 to possibly relocate the knight to c5 through b7. }
*

