[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "2.g3 - 6.d3 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6 4. Nf3
{ As explained in the introduction, White can't just allow Black to push ...d5 and enjoy a stable and superior center.   This and  4.d4  @@StartBracket@@next subchapter@@EndBracket@@ are the options to counter this plan. }
4... e4
{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. d3
{ Right away is one option. In any case, White needs to break the center so Black's temporary space advantage doesn't become a long-term one. }
6... Bc5
{ My preference. Other moves lead to different pawn structures which seem to favour White. }
7. Nb3 Bb4+
{ 7...Bb6?!  has been played in a high level game, but I do not think that Black had equalized.  8.cxd5  Qxd5  9.Nc3  Qf5  10.O-O  exd3  11.e4  Qh5  12.Qxh5  Nxh5  13.Rd1  should also be a bit better for White: Black is behind in development and two developed black pieces are misplaced: the knight on h5 is out of play and the bishop on b6 won't help to stop ideas like Bf4-Bd6; and Na4 may be played at any moment.   9.O-O  Qf5  10.Nc3  exd3  11.e4  is typical when Black takes on d3. White chooses the dynamic e2-e4 rather than the slow exd3, after which he would have an isolated pawn on d3, and Black would be in time to castle. After e2-e4, the d3-pawn will fall anyway.  11...Qh5  12.Qxh5  Nxh5  @@StartSquare@@0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Ding Liren @@StartBracket@@2805@@EndBracket@@-Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2774@@EndBracket@@ Cupar 2019@@EndSquare@@ and here after  13.Na4  the d3-pawn will fall and Black will have a very difficult endgame. }
8. Bd2 a5 { The active option. } 9. O-O exd3 10. Bxb4 axb4 11. Qxd3 dxc4 12.
Qxc4 Na6
{ I believe Black is better. He will play ...Be6 and his pawn on b4 prevents White from developing naturally with Nc3. }
