[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "2.g3 - 6.d3 #1| Alternative 6...exd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6 4. Nf3
{ As explained in the introduction, White can't just allow Black to push ...d5 and enjoy a stable and superior center.   This and  4.d4  @@StartBracket@@next subchapter@@EndBracket@@ are the options to counter this plan. }
4... e4
{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. d3
{ Right away is one option. In any case, White needs to break the center so Black's temporary space advantage doesn't become a long-term one. }
6... exd3
{ May lead to an unclear position after a sequence of forced moves.   6...dxc4  7.dxe4  Bc5  8.e3  Nbd7  9.f4  isn't something we're willing to face, as White has a powerful center and is going to push e5 very soon.   6...Bb4+  In an online 4NCL rapid game I've played this move but ended up much worse anyway, as it turned out Nb1-c3 was a useful move for White, and the black bishop wasn't really adequately placed on b4 since we aren't willing to give away to bishop pair.  7.Nc3  O-O  8.O-O  dxc4  9.dxe4  Qe7  10.Nf5  gave me the opportunity to simplify the position and get reasonable squares for all of my pieces.  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  Nbd7  0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Gourlay, I @@StartBracket@@2342@@EndBracket@@-Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2645@@EndBracket@@ lichess.org 2020. Now if White wants to push his center, he will have to move his f2-pawn, thus weakening his own king.   7...exd3  8.Qxd3  did not satisfy me either: what is the bishop doing on b4?   10.Qc2  Both sides have doubled pawns, but the black ones have no potential  (even managing to push ...b5 and ...b4 would only weaken the c4-pawn)  while the white ones give White a powerful center, with f4 and e5 to come soon or late. }
7. cxd5 { 7.Qxd3  may require attention though. } 7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 c5
{ Black is pushing the white pieces downwards but they'll quickly bounce back. }
9. Nb3 c4 10. Nd2 O-O 11. O-O
{ And already Black needs to take action so he doesn't lose his central pawns and end up with under-developed queenside. }
11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bg4
{ 12...dxe2  13.Qxe2  Nxd5  would keep an extra pawn, but White's coordination would be excellent and Black would be somehow paralyzed:  14.Ba3  Re8  15.Qf3  Nb6  16.Ne4  and White has a powerful activity, with a rook coming to d1 and the e4-knight coming to d6. }
13. f3 Nxd5
{ The only way to complicate the position and avoid simplification that favors White, thanks to his bishop pair and dynamic position. Now Black sacrifices a piece but he is the one attacking.   13...dxe2  14.Qxe2  Bf5  15.Nxc4  Qxd5  16.Rd1  is just a clear advantage for White, who has the bishop pair and his knight coming to d6: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@87@@EndBracket@@ Ding Liren @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@-Inarkiev, E @@StartBracket@@2727@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2017. }
14. fxg4 { White needs to accept the gift: what else to play? } 14... Nxc3 15.
Qe1 Nxe2+ 16. Kh1
{ And although the engine wants Ba3 next and claims a slight advantage for White, the position looks like a real mess, Black having far advanced c and d-pawns, a strong knight on e2 and a great space advantage.   Of course, White's strong bishops @@StartBracket@@on a3 and g3@@EndBracket@@ make the position difficult to play for both sides! }
16... c3 17. Ba3 { Other moves are just better for Black. } 17... Re8
{ 17...cxd2  18.Qxd2 } 18. Qf2 Qd7 { The only move. } 19. Ne4 Nc6
{ Again the only moves. Now, if both players play the best moves, the final position gives a small advantage for White. But the whole line is simply inhuman. }
20. Nc5 Qd6 21. Qxf7+ Kh8 22. Qf5 Qh6 { 22...d2  23.Ne4 } 23. Qxd3 Re3 24. Bc1
{ The point. } 24... Nxg3+ 25. Kg1 Nxf1 26. Qxf1 Nd4 27. Kh1 Nc2
{ There isn't much to comment here: if Black doesn't find these moves, he is lost according to the engine.   28.Bxe3  Nxe3  29.Qf3  Nxg2  30.Kxg2  Qd2+  31.Kh1  c2  32.Nb3  Qd6  33.Rf1  h6  And Black has chances to hold. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "2.g3 - 6.d3 #2 | Alternative 6...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6 4. Nf3
{ As explained in the introduction, White can't just allow Black to push ...d5 and enjoy a stable and superior center.   This and  4.d4  @@StartBracket@@next subchapter@@EndBracket@@ are the options to counter this plan. }
4... e4
{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. d3
{ Right away is one option. In any case, White needs to break the center so Black's temporary space advantage doesn't become a long-term one. }
6... Qb6
{ Doesn't equalize according to the following games:   6...dxc4  7.dxe4  Bc5  8.e3  Nbd7  9.f4  isn't something we're willing to face, as White has a powerful center and is going to push e5 very soon.   6...Bb4+  In an online 4NCL rapid game I've played this move but ended much worse anyway, as it turned out Nb1-c3 was a useful move for White, and the black bishop wasn't really adequately placed on b4 since we aren't willing to give away to bishop pair.  7.Nc3  O-O  8.O-O  dxc4  9.dxe4  Qe7  10.Nf5  gave me the opportunity to simplify the position and get reasonable squares for all of my pieces.  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  Nbd7  0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Gourlay, I @@StartBracket@@2342@@EndBracket@@-Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2645@@EndBracket@@ lichess.org 2020. Now if White wants to push his center, he will have to move his f2-pawn, thus weakening his own king.   7...exd3  8.Qxd3  did not satisfy me either: what is the bishop doing on b4?   10.Qc2  Both sides have doubled pawns, but the black ones have no potential  (even managing to push ...b5 and ...b4 would only weaken the c4-pawn)  while the white ones give White a powerful center, with f4 and e5 to come soon or late. }
7. Nb3
{ 7.dxe4  Bc5  8.e3  dxe4  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  With a double threat of Nxe4 and Ne4 White seems a bit better: ½-½ @@StartBracket@@82@@EndBracket@@Shankland, S @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@-Piorun, K @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Matanzas 2017. }
7... dxc4
{ Black does not want to allow cxd5 followed by dxe4, after what he would end up with a weakness on e4 and White's position would be completely healthy. By exchanging on c4 first, White also has a weakness, the c4-pawn. }
8. dxc4 Qb4+ 9. Nc3
{ When Black takes on c4 White will recover the pawn with Nd2xe4. } 9... Be7
10. O-O Qxc4
{ 10...O-O  11.Qc2  Qxc4  Black collects a pawn but again loses it back right away.  12.Nd2  Qe6  13.Ndxe4  Nxe4  14.Bxe4  White was slightly better in the game Nihal, S @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@-Inarkiev, E @@StartBracket@@2693@@EndBracket@@ Konya 2019, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@.   That sort of pawn structure is generally only a very tiny bit better for White, but here Black is underdeveloped, and he still has to lose one tempo to defend his h7-pawn. The e6-queen is also misplaced as it blocks the c8-bishop. }
11. Nd2
{ Followed by Ndxe4 would just make White's life easier, as the knight would already be excellently placed on e4, being centralized and soon or late targeting the c5/ d6 squares.   White could also have considered  11.Bg5!?  with the idea that  11...O-O  would be answered by  12.Nxe4  , the e7-bishop not being protected. }
11... Qe6 { With equality according to the computer. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "2.g3 - 6.cxd5 Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 { Let's first examine positions without Nc3. } 3...
c6 4. Nf3
{ As explained in the introduction, White can't just allow Black to push ...d5 and enjoy a stable and superior center.   This and  4.d4  @@StartBracket@@next subchapter@@EndBracket@@ are the options to counter this plan. }
4... e4
{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. cxd5 Qb6
{ The best line, as the following variations prove.   We do want to take back on d5 with the pawn, but first we want to disturb the knight on d4, as it would stand on a nice outpost if Black takes ...cxd5 too quickly. The job couldn't be done with ...Bc5 as after Nb3 the black bishop would have been hanging.   6...cxd5?!  is not something I like either, for the reasons explained above:  7.d3  Bc5  8.Nb3  Bb4+  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  Re8  11.Be3  and I think the tension in the center favours White.   6...Qxd5  7.e3  leads to position I dislike, where White will open the center with Nc3 and d3, breaking the center and enjoying a lead in development: Black has moved his queens too many times! }
7. Nb3
{ 7.e3  cxd5  isn't a problem: the e3-pawn limits the c1-bishop and Black has nothing to worry about.   7.Qa4  Bc5  8.dxc6  O-O  9.e3  Rd8  and White is in trouble! His light squares are too weak. }
7... a5 { Threatening to trap the b3-knight with ...a4. } 8. a4 Nxd5
{ Active chess! Black sacrifices the e4-pawn to get a wonderfully active position.   8...cxd5  9.O-O  Na6  isn't any good, as Black is behind in development and after White breaks the center with  10.d3  , he will target Black's central pawns and have perfect squares for his pieces: Be3, Nc3, Nd4, Ndb5... }
9. O-O
{ 9.Bxe4  Bh3  would be a dream for Black: White being unable to castle. } 9...
Be6
{ Black needs to act dynamically. It looks to me like other moves do not equalize.   9...Nf6  to play ...Be6 next looks clever, but after  10.d4  Be6  11.N3d2  solves all the problems tactically, and after  11...Qxd4  12.Nxe4  Qxd1  13.Nxf6+  gxf6  14.Rxd1  Nd7  15.Be3  he just stands a bit better thanks to Black's doubled f-pawns.   A slow continuation would give White a more pleasant position, for example,  9...Be7  10.Na3  O-O  11.Nc4!   11.Bxe4  Nf6!  followed by ...Na6 is Bc2, or otherwise by ...Bh3 or ...Bh6, and Black has good compensation for the same reasons as after 9...Be6.  11...Qa6  is forced,  otherwise the e4–pawn is lost without compensation, as the b3–knight is no longer in danger.  12.d3  exd3  13.exd3↑  and despite a better pawn structure, the queen on a6 is very much out of play. }
10. Bxe4 { Now several moves lead to nice compensation. } 10... Nf6
{ 10...h5  11.d4  Nf6  12.Bc2  h4  with the idea of ...Na6-b4 would also be interesting: one does not play g3-Bg2 to end up with his bishop on c2! Obviously, White's king is very much weakened due to that misplaced bishop.   10...f5!?  would force White to take a decision with his bishop before moving the d5-knight, which could be a great advantage since after Bc2 Black will then be able to jump to b4. However, fortunately for White, he can play  11.Bxf5□  Bxf5  12.e4!  and after  12...Be6!  13.exd5  Bxd5  14.Re1+  Kf7  the position is a big mess, for example,  15.Re3  Nd7  16.d4  Bb4  and the position is just very difficult to assess, the engine giving around equality. White has an extra pawn but he is under-developed and Black has a powerful bishop on d5. }
11. Bc2 Na6 12. d4 Nb4 13. N1d2 h5
{ White is missing his fianchetto bishop so Black starts an attack. It is clear that White couldn't put his pieces on the desired square and that Black enjoys excellent coordination and compensation. }
*

