{ There is no good way to just protect the e5-pawn, so Black pushes it. } 5.
Nd4 d5
{ Black takes control of the center but White managed to disturb it first, and now gets a knight on d4 and the possibility to hit the center with d2-d3. }
6. cxd5 Qb6
{ The best line, as the following variations prove.   We do want to take back on d5 with the pawn, but first we want to disturb the knight on d4, as it would stand on a nice outpost if Black takes ...cxd5 too quickly. The job couldn't be done with ...Bc5 as after Nb3 the black bishop would have been hanging.   6...cxd5?!  is not something I like either, for the reasons explained above:  7.d3  Bc5  8.Nb3  Bb4+  9.Nc3  O-O  10.O-O  Re8  11.Be3  and I think the tension in the center favours White.   6...Qxd5  7.e3  leads to position I dislike, where White will open the center with Nc3 and d3, breaking the center and enjoying a lead in development: Black has moved his queens too many times! }
7. Nb3
{ 7.e3  cxd5  isn't a problem: the e3-pawn limits the c1-bishop and Black has nothing to worry about.   7.Qa4  Bc5  8.dxc6  O-O  9.e3  Rd8  and White is in trouble! His light squares are too weak. }
7... a5 { Threatening to trap the b3-knight with ...a4. } 8. d3
{ Critical. White should react in the center.   8.d4  cxd5  9.Nc3  Be6  is just fine for Black, who has no weakness, more space, and nothing to worry about. }
8... a4 9. N3d2 { 9.Be3?!  c5  and ...Qxb2 next. } 9... exd3 10. O-O
{ The critical move, trying to take advantage of White's lead in development.   10.exd3  Bg4  is also worth a look, as White cannot give a check on the e-file!   10...cxd5  11.O-O  Nc6  will transpose. }
10... cxd5 { It's time to recover the pawn. } 11. exd3
{ White has a small lead in development @@StartBracket@@though his queenside remains undeveloped so far@@EndBracket@@ but he isn't able to take advantage of it, despite being able to check the black king. If Black can complete his development, which he does, he won't have anything to worry about. }
11... Nc6 12. Nc3 { Attacking a4 and d5. } 12... Qa5 { Protecting both pawns! }
13. Re1+ Be6 { The most precise, due to the beautiful idea just below. } 14. a3
{ White must start to establish a plan with b4 in order to develop his dark-squared bishop on b2. }
14... Be7
{ The safest bet.  14...Bc5  is more aggressive but after  15.Nf3  d4  16.Ne4  Nxe4  17.Rxe4  O-O  White can play  18.Rxe6!?  fxe6  19.Ng5  with interesting compensation. After  19...Nd8  the position is a mess, White definitely enjoying good play on the light squares but being an exchange down. }
15. b4 axb3 16. Bb2 O-O 17. Nxb3 Qb6
{ The position is unclear. Black doesn't have any particular weakness and he is threatening ... d4 attacking both of Black's knights. }
18. Ne2 { This should be best. } 18... Ng4 19. d4 Na5
{ Going for the bishop pair. } 20. Nxa5 Qxb2 21. Rb1 Qxa3 22. Nxb7 Bf5
{ And Black is at least without problems. } *

