7. Nb3
{ 7.e3  cxd5  isn't a problem: the e3-pawn limits the c1-bishop and Black has nothing to worry about.   7.Qa4  Bc5  8.dxc6  O-O  9.e3  Rd8  and White is in trouble! His light squares are too weak. }
7... a5 { Threatening to trap the b3-knight with ...a4. } 8. d3
{ Critical. White should react in the center.   8.d4  cxd5  9.Nc3  Be6  is just fine for Black, who has no weakness, more space, and nothing to worry about. }
8... a4 9. N3d2 { 9.Be3?!  c5  and ...Qxb2 next. } 9... exd3 10. O-O
{ The critical move, trying to take advantage of White's lead in development.   10.exd3  Bg4  is also worth a look, as White cannot give a check on the e-file!   10...cxd5  11.O-O  Nc6  will transpose. }
10... cxd5 { It's time to recover the pawn. } 11. exd3
{ White has a small lead in development @@StartBracket@@though his queenside remains undeveloped so far@@EndBracket@@ but he isn't able to take advantage of it, despite being able to check the black king. If Black can complete his development, which he does, he won't have anything to worry about. }
11... Nc6 12. Nc3 { Attacking a4 and d5. } 12... Qa5 { Protecting both pawns! }
13. Re1+ Be6 { The most precise, due to the beautiful idea just below. } 14.
Bh3 { The most natural 'try' against 13...Be6. } 14... Be7
{ A very interesting gambit. Black will have plenty of counterplay on the f-file!   14...Nd8!?  is playable as well. }
15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Rxe6 O-O 17. d4
{ Otherwise Black plays ...d4 himself and enjoys nice compensation. } 17... Bb4
{ Black is doing alright: next could be ...Bxc3, a3, ...Nxd4... White is a little bit stuck on the queenside. }
