[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.d4"]
[Black "4.d4 e4 5.d5 Bb4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. d4 e4
{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. d5
{ Didn't have any special reputation as it had been see in only about 20% of the existing games. However, it's been played by Nihal recently, which means it deserves high attention. Anyhow, I believe it does not cause special problems to Black. }
5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qe7
{ Now White has two ways to play: Nc3-Nh3 plans, or the new trend, e3-Ne2.   The first plan has the advantage of keeping the pawn structure intact, but the knight on h3 is a little awkward. The second is more harmonious, getting the g1-knight towards the center, but weakens the light squares. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. a3 Bxc3
{ I believe this is an interesting approach.   8...Bc5  9.e3  d6  10.Nge2  cxd5  11.Nxd5  making room for the bishop on c3, was more pleasant for White after  11...Nxd5  12.cxd5  Nd7  13.O-O  Nf6  14.Bc3  in the game Carlsen, M  @@StartBracket@@2733@@EndBracket@@-Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2799@@EndBracket@@ Nice 2008, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bxc3 cxd5 10. cxd5 d6 11. Nh3 Nbd7 12. O-O a5
{ Followed by ...Nc5. White has monstruous bishop on c3, but Black has a fair amount of space, a very dynamic position and good play on the light squares @@StartBracket@@e.g. ...Bd7-a4@@EndBracket@@.   If White manages to open the position, Black can be in trouble - but the pawn on e4 is rock-solid and it is actually not easy for White to break Black's setup. I believe the position is unclear.   12...b6  followed by ...Ba6 or ...Bb7 deserves attention as well, in order to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
*

