{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. d5
{ Didn't have any special reputation as it had been see in only about 20% of the existing games. However, it's been played by Nihal recently, which means it deserves high attention. Anyhow, I believe it does not cause special problems to Black. }
5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qe7
{ Now White has two ways to play: Nc3-Nh3 plans, or the new trend, e3-Ne2.   The first plan has the advantage of keeping the pawn structure intact, but the knight on h3 is a little awkward. The second is more harmonious, getting the g1-knight towards the center, but weakens the light squares. }
7. e3 O-O
{ Black is not in a hurry to exchange bishops on d2, as White has shown his intentions were not to play Nc3 - at least not prior to Ne2.   7...Na6  8.Ne2  cxd5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Nbc3  Nf6  11.Nf4  gave White fantastic compensation in the game Abdusattorov, N @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ -Kollars, D @@StartBracket@@2621@@EndBracket@@ Riga 2021, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@80@@EndBracket@@. The d5-square is a serious problem here, and taking on c3 would make White's dark-squared bishop too powerful. So, we'll try to avoid that! }
8. Ne2 a5
{ An interesting move, keeping the tension, while a black pawn on b4 would make White's development much more difficult.   8...cxd5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Qb3  Bxd2+  11.Nxd2  Nf6  12.Nc3  recovering the pawn with a much better pawn structure, is a trick Black should not fall into! }
9. Bc3 d6 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Nbxc3 Re8
{ Followed by ...Nd7, ...Nc5, is just fine for Black. } *

