[White "6) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nc3 d5 6.Bg5 Bb4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. d4 e4
{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 d5 6. Bg5 Bb4
{ Although there are other possible moves, like  6...Nbd7  , my suggestion is to go for this one, the 'normal one', just like if White had exchanged on d5. I believe White makes no benefit in delaying this exchange. }
7. Bxf6 { 7.cxd5  cxd5  is a transposition to the main line. } 7... Qxf6 8. e3
{ An interesting approach for White. By not exchanging pawns on d5, White limits Black development, making the c6-square unavailable for the black knight. However, I do not see it as a problem. }
8... Nd7
{ Although for now the f6-square is occupied by the queen, I recommend to bring the knight to the kingside and believe he's fully in time to do it. }
9. Ne2 O-O
{ In an online game Xiong-Sevian  @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@, Black decided to solve his problems with the d5-pawn playing 9...Nb6, but the knight ended misplaced there. Black's position remained solid, but it was a little bit worse. I will suggest another setup instead.   9...Nb6  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Qb3  Qd6  12.O-O  Bd7  13.a3  Bxc3  14.Nxc3  O-O  15.Rfc1  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Xiong, J @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@-Sevian, S @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ lichess.org 2020. }
10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qb3 Qd6 { The only way to defend the pawn. } 12. O-O Bxc3
{ Better exchange this bishop before it ends up in trouble, as the d6-queen prevents it from moving backwards. }
13. Nxc3 Nf6
{ Black is going to generate counterplay with ...h5, ...h4, and I believe his position is completely fine. }
14. Nb5
{ 14.Rac1  Bd7  with the idea of first consolidating the queenside with ... Bc6, is just fine for Black who will now start playing on the kingside. }
14... Qd8 15. Rac1 h5
{ 15...Bd7?  16.Nc7  and the d5-pawn is lost - and after that the e4-one! } 16.
Nc7 Rb8 17. Rc5 { The only way to increase the pressure.   17.Na6  Ra8= } 17...
Nd7
{ 17...b6  should also be fine, but it creates avoidable holes in the black position. }
18. Rc2 Nf6
{ White has won a tempo, but I do not think he can make serious use of it. }
19. Rfc1
{ 19.h4  Bg4  and White should start being careful: his light squares are seriously weakened. }
19... g6 20. Rc5 Kg7
{ I love this idea. Now the d5-pawn is untouchable because of ...Be6, when Nxf6 won't be a check any more. All White can now do on the queenside is to play }
21. Ra5
{ To win the a7-pawn, but Black will have enough compensation for it, as ...Kg7 also enables the f8-rook to go to h8 attack the white king. }
21... h4 22. Rxa7 hxg3 23. fxg3 Rh8
{ With the threat of ...Ng4 is even worse. } *

