[Round "?"]
[White "6) English 2.g3, 3.Bg2 and 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nc3 d5 6.Bg5 Bb4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. d4 e4
{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 d5 6. Bg5 Bb4
{ Although there are other possible moves, like  6...Nbd7  , my suggestion is to go for this one, the 'normal one', just like if White had exchanged on d5. I believe White makes no benefit in delaying this exchange. }
7. Qb3 Bxc3+
{ The good reaction. This knight must anyhow be eliminated to avoid problems with the d5-pawn. }
8. bxc3
{ This recapture, which at first may seem good to break Black's center with cxd5 followed by c4, is simply bad for White who will end up in a worse position. }
8... Nbd7 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. f3
{ 10.e3?!  just makes White's position even worse, with more problems on the a6-f1 diagonal.  10...O-O  11.Ne2  h6  12.Bxf6  Nxf6  13.O-O  b6  . }
10... h6 11. Bc1
{ 11.Bxf6  Nxf6  12.Nh3  O-O  0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Brunner, L @@StartBracket@@2452@@EndBracket@@-Edouard, R @@StartBracket@@2658@@EndBracket@@ Switzerland 2019. There isn't much to comment on here: Black has zero problems and the white pieces are highly passive. Black should only decide whether he wants to take on f3 or try ...e3, both being good choices. }
11... O-O 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Nh3 Nb6 14. O-O Be6
{ Black is already positionally winning thanks to the weakness of the light squares for White: 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Turner, M @@StartBracket@@2524@@EndBracket@@-Le Roux, J @@StartBracket@@2539@@EndBracket@@ Telford 2019. }
*

