[Black "5.Nc3 d5 6.a3 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. d4 e4
{ While  4...exd4  is a very reliable alternative with the white knight on c3, here it is much less to the point.  The main reason in that in positions with an isolated pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@e.g.  5.Qxd4  d5  6.cxd5  cxd5  @@EndBracket@@ White will play  7.Nf3  and O-O shortly, and Black won't have ...Nc6 followed by ...d4 to generate quick counterplay against the knight on c3. }
5. Nc3 d5 6. a3 { Another way to prevent ... Bb4. } 6... Be7
{ The easiest. White's goal is no longer to play Bg5 @@StartBracket@@that would be too slow due to ...Nbd7, ...h6@@EndBracket@@ but to break the center with f3, so there is no reason to lose time with ...h6 for now. }
7. f3 exf3 8. Nxf3 O-O 9. O-O h6
{ 9...dxc4  10.e4  b5  is also possible, but obviously gives White interesting compensation with a powerful center. }
10. Nh4 dxc4
{ Now I believe Black should take, as contrarily to positions with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2bpp1/2p2n1p/3p4/2PP4/P1N2NP1/1P2P1BP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.cxd5  cxd5  included, he won't be able to develop  easily with ...Nc6. }
11. e4 c5 12. d5 Bd6
{ Followed by either ...Ng4 or ...Nbd7, and as long as Black can stop e4-e5, he's doing alright. }
13. Bf4
{ Perhaps White's best try. White should try everything to unlock the dark squares. }
13... Bxf4 14. Rxf4 { 14.gxf4?  Nxe4 } 14... Nbd7
{ 14...g5  15.Rf1  gxh4  16.e5!  followed by Ne4 would be highly risky for Black - though probably fine as well. }
15. Qd2 Ne5 16. Raf1 Ne8 17. Nf3 Qe7 18. d6
{ If White allows ...Nd6 he is just positionally lost. } 18... Qxd6
{ 18...Nxd6  19.Nd5  Nxf3+  20.R4xf3  Qd8  21.Nf6+  is a mess that I would suggest to avoid, although nothing disastrous. }
19. Qxd6 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Nxd6 21. e5 g5
{ The most forcing, although  21...Nf5  is fine as well. } 22. Rf6 Nf5 23. Bxb7
Bxb7 24. R1xf5 Kg7 25. h4 gxh4 26. Rf4 hxg3 27. Rg4+ Kh7 28. Rh4 Kg7
{ With a likely draw. } *

