[White "7) English 2.g3, 3.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 e4 - 6.Nc2 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Nf3
{ Again, White should prevent Black from playing ...d5 comfortably and get a very stable center. }
4... e4 5. Nd4 Qb6
{ The best move order, disturbing the placement of the d4-knight.   5...d5  is a worse move order.  6.cxd5  Qb6  7.Nb3  a5  trying to play as in our main line.  8.d3  a4  9.Nd2  exd3  .  And here comes the difference.  10.Nc4  and White will be able to recapture on d3 with his queen. Black will remain undeveloped and with a weak isolated pawn on d5.   6...cxd5  7.d3  Bc5  8.dxe4  dxe4  9.Be3  would just be good for White - the knight on d4 is excellently placed, and it's clear Black should have done something against it earlier.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp2n2/3P4/4p3/1NN3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd5  8.Bg2  White will push d3 next and Black isn't in time to disturb White's pieces coordination as in our main line, e.g.  8...Nc6  9.d3  exd3  10.Bg5  and again, Black has concrete problems with his d5-pawn.   8...Be7  9.d3  exd3  10.Qxd3  and Black is worse due to his isolated d5-pawn. }
6. Nc2 { The other natural square for the white knight to move to. } 6... d5
{ Here White can decide to exchange pawns on d5 or to postpone it. } 7. Bg2
dxc4
{ I like this sharp alternative.   A developing move like  7...Be6  or  7...Be7  would be possible as well. }
8. Nxe4 { Capturing the central pawn is the first thing to look at. } 8... Nxe4
9. Bxe4 Na6
{ 9...Bh3  is tempting, but after  10.Ne3  followed by Qc2, the c4-pawn will be lost, and White will most probably get rid off the h3-bishop with Bf5. This is not what Black wants. }
10. O-O Nc5 11. Bg2 Be7
{ Generally, when Black captures on pawn on c4 in that type of pawn structure, the pawn is considered a weakness. However, here, it paralyzes White and can easily be defended @@StartBracket@@...Be6, and a queen move if necessary@@EndBracket@@. The best White can do is to trade pawn, leading to an equal position. }
12. d3 cxd3 13. exd3 O-O 14. d4 Na6
{ If Black can play ...Nc7 and stop d5, he will be slightly better. } 15. d5
cxd5 16. Ne3
{ White would like to capture on d5 with his knight, and he will, but of course Black won't let the knight alive on d5. }
16... Nc7 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Be6
{ A typical sacrifice. Black loses the b7-pawn, but b2 is going to fall as well. }
19. Qxb7 Qxb7 20. Bxb7 Rab8 21. Bf3 Bf6 { Here we have a total equality. } *

