{ The best move order, disturbing the placement of the d4-knight.   5...d5  is a worse move order.  6.cxd5  Qb6  7.Nb3  a5  trying to play as in our main line.  8.d3  a4  9.Nd2  exd3  .  And here comes the difference.  10.Nc4  and White will be able to recapture on d3 with his queen. Black will remain undeveloped and with a weak isolated pawn on d5.   6...cxd5  7.d3  Bc5  8.dxe4  dxe4  9.Be3  would just be good for White - the knight on d4 is excellently placed, and it's clear Black should have done something against it earlier.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp2n2/3P4/4p3/1NN3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd5  8.Bg2  White will push d3 next and Black isn't in time to disturb White's pieces coordination as in our main line, e.g.  8...Nc6  9.d3  exd3  10.Bg5  and again, Black has concrete problems with his d5-pawn.   8...Be7  9.d3  exd3  10.Qxd3  and Black is worse due to his isolated d5-pawn. }
6. Nc2 { The other natural square for the white knight to move to. } 6... d5
