[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) English 2.g3, 3.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "6.Nb3 a5 7.d3 a4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Nf3
{ Again, White should prevent Black from playing ...d5 comfortably and get a very stable center. }
4... e4 5. Nd4 Qb6
{ The best move order, disturbing the placement of the d4-knight.   5...d5  is a worse move order.  6.cxd5  Qb6  7.Nb3  a5  trying to play as in our main line.  8.d3  a4  9.Nd2  exd3  .  And here comes the difference.  10.Nc4  and White will be able to recapture on d3 with his queen. Black will remain undeveloped and with a weak isolated pawn on d5.   6...cxd5  7.d3  Bc5  8.dxe4  dxe4  9.Be3  would just be good for White - the knight on d4 is excellently placed, and it's clear Black should have done something against it earlier.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp2n2/3P4/4p3/1NN3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd5  8.Bg2  White will push d3 next and Black isn't in time to disturb White's pieces coordination as in our main line, e.g.  8...Nc6  9.d3  exd3  10.Bg5  and again, Black has concrete problems with his d5-pawn.   8...Be7  9.d3  exd3  10.Qxd3  and Black is worse due to his isolated d5-pawn. }
6. Nb3 a5
{ Black wants to disturb the white piece coordination before he is no longer in time to do it.   Here  7.--  a4  is a serious threat. }
7. d3 a4 8. Nd2 exd3
{ It's time to accept this exchange before White takes a central pawn for free! This is a line which I just worked on in 2012, when working for Topalov in Wijk aan Zee.   At the time, the line was unknown and Nakamura fell into the trick, recapturing on d3 right away. }
9. Bg2 d5
{ Black needs to play active, as for the moment he is underdeveloped and his pawn on a4 can be taken. }
10. exd3 Bg4
{ The critical move, taking advantage of the fact White is here unable to deliver a check on the e-file @@StartBracket@@unless he wants to give us a free queen!@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bf3
{ This was played in the only existing game in this position. I was playing Black against Sébastien Mazé. The game was played in 2012 - the year I became French Champion! }
11... Bh3
{ The less aggressive alternative  11...Bxf3  12.Nxf3  d4  13.Ne2  c5  14.Bg5  Nbd7  15.Nf4  Be7  also seems to be okay for Black. }
12. cxd5 Be7
{ Here we don't dare about the d5-pawn nor the a4-one, we just want to castle and punish the white king in the center! }
13. Nc4 { 13.d6  Bxd6  14.Nc4  is just a transposition. } 13... Qd8 14. d6
{ The best defense. } 14... Bxd6 15. Nxd6+ Qxd6 16. Qe2+
{ Now Black has a choice whether to keep queens or not, and both are okay.   The same choice applies if White chooses  16.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@  16...Qe6+  or  16...Qd8  @@EndBracket@@. }
16... Be6
{ Black decides to keep queens on the board.   16...Qe6  17.Qxe6+  Bxe6  And Black will castle shortside, play ...Rd8, ...Na6, then possibly ...Nb4. He is perfectly fine here.   17...fxe6  which wasn't bad either. Of course, I am deliberately choosing to weaken my pawn structure to keep the white king in the center.   Nevertheless, although e6 is weak, I get an extra square on d5 for my knight, while the other one is likely to develop through a6. Some 22 moves later the game ended in a draw.   Note the engine rates both  17...Bxe6  and  17...fxe6  as equal.   1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Maze,S @@StartBracket@@2573@@EndBracket@@ -Edouard,R @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@ Pau 2012 }
17. Bf4 Qd8 18. O-O O-O 19. Rfe1 Nbd7 20. Bg2 Re8
{ And again, Black is perfectly fine. His next moves could be ...Nb6-Nbd5, or ...Qa5, ...Qh5. Exchange the light-squared bishops would be a dream, in order to set a powerful knight on d5. But here, objectively speaking, the bishop pair compensates the weakness on d3. }
