1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Nf3
{ Again, White should prevent Black from playing ...d5 comfortably and get a very stable center. }
4... e4 5. Nd4 Qb6
{ The best move order, disturbing the placement of the d4-knight.   5...d5  is a worse move order.  6.cxd5  Qb6  7.Nb3  a5  trying to play as in our main line.  8.d3  a4  9.Nd2  exd3  .  And here comes the difference.  10.Nc4  and White will be able to recapture on d3 with his queen. Black will remain undeveloped and with a weak isolated pawn on d5.   6...cxd5  7.d3  Bc5  8.dxe4  dxe4  9.Be3  would just be good for White - the knight on d4 is excellently placed, and it's clear Black should have done something against it earlier.   @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qp2n2/3P4/4p3/1NN3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd5  8.Bg2  White will push d3 next and Black isn't in time to disturb White's pieces coordination as in our main line, e.g.  8...Nc6  9.d3  exd3  10.Bg5  and again, Black has concrete problems with his d5-pawn.   8...Be7  9.d3  exd3  10.Qxd3  and Black is worse due to his isolated d5-pawn. }
6. Nb3 a5
{ Black wants to disturb the white piece coordination before he is no longer in time to do it.   Here  7.--  a4  is a serious threat. }
7. d3 a4 8. Nd2 exd3
{ It's time to accept this exchange before White takes a central pawn for free! This is a line which I just worked on in 2012, when working for Topalov in Wijk aan Zee.   At the time, the line was unknown and Nakamura fell into the trick, recapturing on d3 right away. }
9. Bg2 d5
{ Black needs to play active, as for the moment he is underdeveloped and his pawn on a4 can be taken. }
10. cxd5 cxd5
{ 10...Bb4?  was played by Etienne Bacrot, but is just bad:  11.O-O  O-O  12.Nc4  and White was already winning: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2778@@EndBracket@@-Bacrot,E @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@ SUI 2012. }
11. O-O { Critical. } 11... Bg4 { My favorite. } 12. h3
{ White should force exchanges on e2, otherwise he'll never be able to take advantage of his lead in development. }
12... Bxe2 13. Nxe2 dxe2 14. Qxe2+ Be7
{ Black is on the limit of having serious problems - but it all works for him. }
15. Re1
{ 15.b4  With this clever move, White wants to gain space, and make b5 possible when the black knight is on c6 e.g.  15...Nc6  16.a3  O-O?  17.b5  .   15...axb3  16.Nxb3  Nc6  Black will manage to castle and White has compensation for the pawn, but no more than that. A likely outcome is that White recovers the pawn and the game ends up in a draw.   15...Qxb4?  16.Rb1  followed by Rxb7 would be disastrous for Black.   @@StartFEN@@rn2k2r/1p2bppp/1q3n2/3p4/8/1p4PP/P2NQPB1/R1B2RK1 w kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Rb1?  doesn't work due to  16...Rxa2  17.Rxb3  Qxb3  . }
15... Nc6 16. Nc4 { The knight is untouchable due to Bxc6+ followed by Qxe7. }
16... Qc5 17. Ne5 Nd4 18. Qd1 Ne6
{ And White has compensation, but no more than that.   18...Nc2  19.Nd3  Qc6  and here White loses an exchange, but can sacrifice it with  20.Rxe7+  offering him great compensation after  20...Kxe7  21.Ne5  Qc5  22.Nd3  Qc6  23.Rb1  Rhc8  24.Bd2  when Black's position looks more than risky, as the knight on c2 could be in trouble if Black only focuses on his king. }
