1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. d4 exd4
{ Although  4...e4  is playable here too, with the knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@instead of Bg2@@EndBracket@@ I would advice to capture on d4, for a reason I've explained earlier: in isolated pawn positions, ...Nc6 and ...d4 will be much more disturbing with a white knight on c3, not talking about the delayed development of the white kingside. }
5. Qxd4 d5 6. Bg2 Be6
{ Best and easiest in my opinion. Black forces White to take a decision in the center. }
7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Qa4 Bb4 10. O-O
{ White doesn't try to take advantage of the pinned c6-knight and simply castles. }
10... O-O 11. Be3 Bxc3
{ Here  11...d4  wouldn't work was White would just play  12.Nxd4  and the bishop on b4 would be hanging. }
12. bxc3 Ne4
{ Followed by ...Qa5, ...Rc8, and we get a typical Ragozin pawn structure when the weakness of the c3-pawn and the c4-square compensate for the bishop pair and the isolated pawn on d5. Black is fine. }
