{ Although  4...e4  is playable here too, with the knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@instead of Bg2@@EndBracket@@ I would advice to capture on d4, for a reason I've explained earlier: in isolated pawn positions, ...Nc6 and ...d4 will be much more disturbing with a white knight on c3, not talking about the delayed development of the white kingside. }
5. Qxd4 d5 6. Bg2 Be6
{ Best and easiest in my opinion. Black forces White to take a decision in the center. }
7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Qa4 Bb4 10. Nd4
{ Instead,  10.Ne5  would likely transpose after Black takes on c3 and castles, and White takes on c6. }
10... O-O
{ Black doesn't fear losing on pawn on c6, nor losing the bishop pair with  11.Nxe6  . }
11. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 bxc6 13. O-O Ne4
{ The simplest, although  13...Qc8!?  is possible as well. Now the queen rather aims at going to f6.   Black makes a typical pawn sacrifice to take away White's fianchettoed bishop, meaning White will suffer on the light squares after capturing the pawn. }
14. c4
