[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 c6 4. d4 exd4
{ Although  4...e4  is playable here too, with the knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@instead of Bg2@@EndBracket@@ I would advice to capture on d4, for a reason I've explained earlier: in isolated pawn positions, ...Nc6 and ...d4 will be much more disturbing with a white knight on c3, not talking about the delayed development of the white kingside. }
5. Qxd4 d5 6. Nf3 Na6
{ Instead,  6...Be6  is fully playable, but this is my favourite. } 7. Bg2
{ 7.cxd5?!  Nb4  threatening ...Nc2+ and followed by ...Nbxd5 is more than fine for Black. }
7... Bc5
{ My advice. If White doesn't give a check on e5, this is just a free tempo! }
8. Qe5+ Be6 9. cxd5 { The start of a total mess. } 9... Bxf2+ 10. Kf1
{ 10.Kxf2??  Ng4+  wins the queen. } 10... cxd5 11. e3
{ White tries to trap the bishop on f2 - the only way to justify all this mess.   Of course not  11.Kxf2??  Ng4+  . }
11... Nc5 12. Nd1 { White goes for the f2-bishop. } 12... Nce4
{ 12...Qa5?  13.Nxf2  Nb3  ,  using the pin of the a-pawn.  14.axb3  Qxa1  15.Ke2  Rc8  .  Here we have a mess as well, but after  16.Bd2  Qa6+  17.Ke1  Qa1+  18.Nd1  O-O  19.h3  White holds everything pretty well and should objectively be clearly better. }
13. Ng5 { The only move not to be much worse. Now Black has several options. }
13... Nd7
{ The most concrete line. I'll give some sample alternatives, but am choosing this one as my main line, as the other moves lead to very blurry position that only an engine really understands! }
14. Qxg7 Qxg5 15. Qxg5 Nxg5 16. Nxf2 Rc8 17. Bd2 Nc5
{ Followed by ...Nge4 is around equal. } *

