1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ There are different possibilities against 2.d3, though this move hides much more venom than you may think at first.   As a matter of consistency, and also because I think it's the best line, I'll suggest playing a reversed Open Sicilian here as well. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here we have a reversed Najdorf Sicilian. } 6. e4
{ Now Black may choose between  6...Nb6  or  6...Nf6  , the first one being more aggressive, the second one more solid. As we are playing a Sicilian a tempo down, I believe it is more sensible to go for a solid and fine position, so that will be my suggestion to you. }
6... Nf6 7. Qc2
{ White prevents ... Bc5, just as Black can play ... Qc7 to prevent Bc4 in similar positions in the Najdorf. }
7... a5 8. Be2 g6
{ A completely brand new plan than White can't do in the reversed situation @@StartBracket@@the Classical Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ because the bishop is already on e2. }
9. O-O Bg7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Nh5
{ Followed by ...Nf4 or ...Nd4. Black has a pleasant position. } *

