1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ There are different possibilities against 2.d3, though this move hides much more venom than you may think at first.   As a matter of consistency, and also because I think it's the best line, I'll suggest playing a reversed Open Sicilian here as well. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ We have a reversed Classical Sicilian! } 6. e4
{ This is supposed to be the best try for White. } 6... Nxc3
{ However, again I believe there's nothing wrong with this pawn structure, even if White's e-pawn is already on e4. }
7. bxc3 Bc5 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Qe7 10. Qc2
{ 10.h3  h6!?  11.Be3  Bb6  and Black could follow up with a calm plan  (...Be6, ...Rad8)  or play ...f5 next, with unclear positions in both cases. }
10... Bg4 11. h3
{ This was played in a game Kramnik-Nakamura in 2019. Here I think a simple solution is: }
11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 b5
{ With the idea of soon pushing ...b4 to take control of the d4-square. } 13.
Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Na5 15. a4 a6 16. Rab1 c6
{ Followed by ...Nb7-d6, and Black is doing perfectly fine: White's only remaining minor piece being his worst one. }
