[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. Nxc6
{ This is definitely not a critical move. } 4... dxc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3
{ A position that GM Rakhmanov played many times, but that seems horrific for White. }
6... Bd6 7. h3 Bf5
{ Instead, Black played  7...h5  twice, but I don't even think it's a necessary move. }
8. Qc2 Qe7 9. b3 O-O-O 10. Bb2
{ The typical way for White to develop: at least his king will be safe on the queenside. White's dream is to play d2-d3 in perfect conditions and end up with a better pawn structure, but Black's position is just too dynamic and White is simply much worse. }
10... Bg6 11. O-O-O Be5
{ With this extra tempo, things go even worse for White. } 12. d4 exd3 13. Bxd3
Rxd3 14. Rxd3 Re8 { Winning of bit of time, with a huge advantage. } 15. Qe2
Bxd3 16. Qxd3 b6
{ Followed by ...g6, ...Kb7, or even ...Bxc3 and ...Ne4 at any moment, possibly even ...a5 to push the pawn even further at some point. White is simply much worse despite a better pawn structure. }
*

