[Black "2.Nf3 e4 - 4.e3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. e3 Nf6
{ Again, not the only move, but I believe the simplest and perhaps best one. }
5. Nxc6
{ Once more White is not in time to coordinate his pieces and take advantage of an more healthy pawn structure. }
5... dxc6 6. d4
{ White pushes his d-pawn before it is too late @@StartBracket@@if Black is in time to play ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@. }
6... exd3 7. Bxd3
{ 7.Qxd3  Bd6  again, the position is very good for Black. White is totally underdeveloped. Next is ...Qe7, ...Be6, and most probably ...O-O-O. White's only develop piece is his queen! }
7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3
{ If  8.Bd2  the light-squared bishop is hanging in d3 allowing  8...Qxd3  9.Bxb4  Qxc4  Black is up a pawn and clearly better. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Be6
{ This is even worse, White ended up with a worse structure  (3 islands)  and will need to find really unnatural moves to maintain equality. Black is on the comfortable side.   The 'natural'  10.Ba3  it's not annoying Black will continue with  10...Nd7  followed by ...Qf6 and castle queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 2.Nf3 e4 Sort of Reversed Alekhine"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e4 - 4.e3 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. e3 Nf6
{ Again, not the only move, but I believe the simplest and perhaps best one. }
5. Nc3 Nxd4 6. exd4 d5
{ This simple and strong move has almost never been played.   6...c6  is just for the anecdote,  one of my first tries.  7.d5  is the critical move. Here, I tried to invent a sort of new 'Bellon Lopez gambit'  (we mentioned it at the start of Part I)  with  7...b5?!  but it turns out that after  8.cxb5  cxd5  9.d3  Black doesn't manage to organize enough counterplay for his damaged pawn structure. }
7. cxd5
{ 7.c5  b6  is also a nonsense for White. Black is just slightly better. } 7...
Nxd5 8. Nxe4 { A huge mistake. } 8... Qe7 9. Qe2
{ And now, while ...Nf4 may not be too dramatic for White, after: } 9... Bf5
10. d3 O-O-O { Black is definitely much better, if not just winning. } *

