[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. e3 Nf6
{ Again, not the only move, but I believe the simplest and perhaps best one. }
5. Nc3 Nxd4 6. exd4 d5
{ This simple and strong move has almost never been played.   6...c6  is just for the anecdote,  one of my first tries.  7.d5  is the critical move. Here, I tried to invent a sort of new 'Bellon Lopez gambit'  (we mentioned it at the start of Part I)  with  7...b5?!  but it turns out that after  8.cxb5  cxd5  9.d3  Black doesn't manage to organize enough counterplay for his damaged pawn structure. }
7. d3
{ 7.Qb3  Bd6  8.cxd5  O-O  and White is in big trouble, being way behind in development. }
7... exd3 8. Bxd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is the only try for White. Black was not in time to play ...h6 as Re1+ would have been quite annoying, but with an extra tempo, ...h6 would solve any kind of problem. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 c6 13. d5 cxd5 14. Nxd5 g5 { The game is completely equal. }
15. Bg3 Bxg3 16. fxg3 { 16.hxg3  Be6= } 16... Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Be6
{ Just trading everything. } 18. Bxe6 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Qxe6
{ With total equallity. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 2.Nf3 e4 Sort of Reversed Alekhine"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e4 - 4.e3 Nf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ I discovered this line when working on this course, and found out that GM Rakhmanov was a big specialist of it. However, with a few precise moves, Black seems to be doing more than fine. }
2... e4
{ We attack the white knight, entering a sort of reversed Alekhine where White will move this knight twice in the opening. }
3. Nd4 Nc6 { The main and best line. } 4. e3 Nf6
{ Again, not the only move, but I believe the simplest and perhaps best one. }
5. Nc3 Nxd4 6. exd4 d5
{ This simple and strong move has almost never been played.   6...c6  is just for the anecdote,  one of my first tries.  7.d5  is the critical move. Here, I tried to invent a sort of new 'Bellon Lopez gambit'  (we mentioned it at the start of Part I)  with  7...b5?!  but it turns out that after  8.cxb5  cxd5  9.d3  Black doesn't manage to organize enough counterplay for his damaged pawn structure. }
7. d3
{ 7.Qb3  Bd6  8.cxd5  O-O  and White is in big trouble, being way behind in development. }
7... exd3 8. Bxd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is the only try for White. Black was not in time to play ...h6 as Re1+ would have been quite annoying, but with an extra tempo, ...h6 would solve any kind of problem. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 c6 13. Re1
{ The best try, I believe. As you can see below, the forcing  13.d5  doesn't lead anywhere, and after any other move Black would just play ...Re8 and ...Be6, with a perfectly fine position. }
13... g5
{ Anyway! The position is concrete and ...g5 happens not to be as weakening as it may look at first sight. }
14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. hxg3
{ And now plenty of moves lead to equality.   15.fxg3  Bf5  hardly makes sense for White, now that his rook is gone from f1. }
15... Bf5
{ Followed by ...Qd6, ...Bg6, ...Rad8, ...Kg7 - White does not have any way to even put a slight pressure on Black.   Other moves like  15...Kg7  would also be completely fine. }
*

