1. c4 e5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This isn't a good approach. Black easily develops his pieces to get a very healthy position. }
4... Bb4
{ The most natural reaction: next is likely to be ...exd4 and ...d5, but even plans like ...Bxc3+ and ...d6 would transpose into some sort of very fine Nimzo-Indian. }
5. d5
{ 5.Nf3  would transpose into  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.e3  Bb4  5.d4  this line from chapter 2 analyzed here. }
5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nb8
{ Black wants to play ...d6, ...Nbd7 and set a very strong knight on c5. } 7.
d6
{ The only way to mess things up, but it's one more pawn move when White still doesn't have a single developed piece. }
7... O-O { Black wants to play ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 or ...Na6-c5. } 8. dxc7
Qxc7 9. Ba3
{ Again trying to mess things up, but keeping the kingside undeveloped. } 9...
Re8 10. Bd6 Qd8
{ Black will just play ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5 and may target the c4-pawn @@StartBracket@@...Bb7, ...Rc8@@EndBracket@@ or the d6-bishop @@StartBracket@@...Ne4 or ...Nb7@@EndBracket@@. White is so undeveloped that it will be a miracle if he doesn't end up clearly worse, not even saying that his only advantage, the bishop pair, is largely compensated by his two doubled isolated c-pawns. }
