1. c4 e5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This isn't a good approach. Black easily develops his pieces to get a very healthy position. }
4... Bb4
{ The most natural reaction: next is likely to be ...exd4 and ...d5, but even plans like ...Bxc3+ and ...d6 would transpose into some sort of very fine Nimzo-Indian. }
5. Ne2
{ 5.a3  Bxc3+  6.bxc3  d6  is just a wonderful Nimzo-Indian for Black. He will play ...O-O and then have several plans, once of them being to play ...Na5, ...b6, ...Ba6, and target the c4-pawn. }
5... exd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5
{ This was played in the only existing game, and by this line's specialist GM Rakhmanov, but White is already LOST! }
7... Nxd5 8. a3 Ba5 9. Qd3
{ 9.b4  Bb6  and White should be happy if he doesn't lose his d4-pawn AND falls under an attack, as he is still far away from castling. }
9... O-O 10. Bd2 Re8
{ 10...Nde7  11.Be3  Bf5  12.Qd2  Bb6  Black will play ...Na5, ... Re8, and White's position is pointless. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ -Sargissian,G @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@ Spain 2015. }
11. O-O-O Be6
{ Was even stronger: ...Nxc3 followed by ...Bb3 may come, and White's position is a horrific disaster. }
