1. c4 e5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Qb3
{ This move, clearly aiming at stopping ...d5, has been played twice by Carlsen. Once in Wijk aan Zee, against Giri in 2020, once in the Gold Money Asian online rapid in 2021, against Ding Liren. It has also been tried by Erigaisi, the recent winner of the Wijk aan Zee Challengers group. }
4... Bb4 { We stick to the same plan. } 5. Nge2
{ White wants to recapture on c3 with the knight - if Black decided to take it. }
5... O-O 6. a3 Bxc3
{ Not a forced move of course, but other options are rather slow, and I'm now going to propose you a plan that has never been played. }
7. Nxc3 Ne7 { Black simply wants to play ...c6 and ...d5. } 8. Be2
{ White needs to develop: any other move would not bring any extra value. }
8... c6 9. O-O Re8
{ Black takes his time before playing ...d5, as if White pushes d4 too early, then after ...d5 cxd5, Black isn't going to recapture with the c-pawn anymore! }
10. d4 exd4 11. exd4 d5 { And Black will just set a knight on d5. } 12. c5 Nf5
{ Followed by ...Ne4. Black is absolutely fine in either case, probably even better in the current position. }
