{ White wants to recapture on c3 with the knight - if Black decided to take it. }
5... O-O 6. a3 Bxc3
{ Not a forced move of course, but other options are rather slow, and I'm now going to propose you a plan that has never been played. }
7. Nxc3 Ne7 { Black simply wants to play ...c6 and ...d5. } 8. Be2
{ White needs to develop: any other move would not bring any extra value. }
8... c6 9. O-O Re8
{ Black takes his time before playing ...d5, as if White pushes d4 too early, then after ...d5 cxd5, Black isn't going to recapture with the c-pawn anymore! }
10. d3 d5
{ Now that White played d3, Black goes for ...d5, as after playing d3-d4 Black will have moved his d-pawn twice instead of once. }
11. cxd5 cxd5 12. d4 e4
{ Similarly to some positions we've seen, Black decides to close the center and play for activity. }
13. Bd2 Nf5 14. a4 h5
{ Black has enough counterplay on the kingside, for example: } 15. a5 Nh4
{ Threatening ...Bg4.   15...Re6?!  16.f3  would be problematic, as suddenly Black is disorganized. }
16. Be1 { Making f2-f3 possible. } 16... Nf5
{ Making f2-f3 impossible, and Black wants to play ...Re6, and the rook could quickly arrive to g6 if White decides to move a single finger.   Objectively, his best option might be to repeat moves with  17.Bd2  . }
*

