{ The position is similar to 4.a3 @@StartBracket@@Chapter 4@@EndBracket@@, except that the white knight hasn't gone to f3 yet. }
6. Qc2 Nxc3
{ The simplest solution, forcing White to decide early on the pawn structure he wants. }
7. bxc3 { 7.dxc3  Bd6  followed by ...O-O, ...f5, can hardly be threatening. }
7... Qg5
{ Just as White often brings his queen to g3 nowadays in the Sicilian, especially in the Taimanov when Black's queen stands on c7, Black not only wants to tease White a little bit with his g2-pawn, but also wants to play ...Qg6 and enter a very reasonable endgame. }
8. Nf3 Qg6 9. d3
{ Keeping queens isn't necessarily a safe bet.   9.Qxg6  hxg6  10.d4  Bd6  and Black is doing completely fine - we've seen similar endgames in 4.a3 lines @@StartBracket@@Chapter 4@@EndBracket@@ . }
9... Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O b6
{ Followed by ...Bb7 is just excellent for Black. } *

