{ The simplest solution, forcing White to decide early on the pawn structure he wants. }
7. Qxc3 Bd6 8. b4 Bd7
{ Was played by Nepomniachtchi against Carlsen in the recent Airthings Masters. Black wants to make ...O-O-O possible and solidifies his position against any Bb5 idea.   Although this move order looks a bit weird to me, even then he had no problem to equalize. }
