3. Bb2 Nbc6 4. Nf3 d5
{ Gambitting the e5-pawn, the following lines will clearly show that the knight is much better placed on e7! }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nxe5
{ Again capturing the pawn will soon turn to a nightmare for White, though not as much as one move earlier. But it is also the only way to justify White's first five moves. }
6... Nxe5 7. Bxe5 Qe7
{ Asking a clear question to the d4-bishop while preparing an attack against the white king, very likely with ...O-O-O involved. }
8. d4 Bf5 9. e4 { White should try to develop, at least. } 9... Bxe4 10. Nd2
O-O-O 11. Nxe4 f6 { And White will be left with a disgusting position again. }
